{"title_page": "Didia (gens)", "text_new": "[[File:T._Didius,_denarius,_113-112_BC,_RRC_294-1.jpg|thumb|300x300px|[[Denarius]] of [[Titus Didius]], minted in 113 or 112 BC. [[Roma (mythology)|Roma]] is portrayed on the obverse, while the reverse depicts two [[Gladiator|gladiators]]. It may represent a political promise from Didius to offer gladiatorial shows, should he be elected [[Aedile|curule aedile]].<ref>Crawford, ''Roman Republican Coinage'', p. 308.</ref>]]\nThe '''gens Didia''', or '''Deidia''', as the name is spelled on coins, was a [[plebs|plebeian]] family at [[Ancient Rome]], which first appears in history during the final century of the [[Roman Republic|Republic]].  According to [[Cicero]], they were ''[[novus homo|novi homines]]''.  [[Titus Didius]] obtained the [[Roman consul|consulship]] in 98 BC, a dignity shared by no other Didii until [[Roman Empire|imperial times]].<ref name=\"DGRBM\">''Dictionary of Greek and Roman Biography and Mythology'', vol. I, p. 1004 (\"Didia Gens\").</ref><ref>Cicero, ''Pro Murena'', 8.</ref>\n\n==Origin==\nThe [[Roman naming conventions#Nomen|nomen]] ''Didius'' or ''Deidius'' is of uncertain origin.  It resembles a class of gentilicia formed from [[cognomen|cognomina]] ending in ''-idus'', but might be derived from a cognomen ''Dida''.  Chase classifies it among those gentilicia that either originated at Rome, or cannot be shown to have come from anywhere else.<ref>Chase, pp. 121, 122, 130.</ref>\n\n==Praenomina==\nThe earlier Didii used the [[praenomen|praenomina]] ''[[Sextus (praenomen)|Sextus]]'', ''[[Titus (praenomen)|Titus]]'', and ''[[Gaius (praenomen)|Gaius]]'', to which later members of the family added ''[[Quintus (praenomen)|Quintus]]'', ''[[Aulus (praenomen)|Aulus]]'', and ''[[Lucius (praenomen)|Lucius]]''.  All of these were common throughout Roman history.\n\n==Branches and cognomina==\nNone of the Didii mentioned during the Republic is known to have borne a cognomen.<ref name=\"DGRBM\"/>  A number of surnames are found under the Empire, of which the only one that appears to be a family name is ''Gallus''.  This cognomen, referring to a cockerel, belongs to an abundant class of cognomina derived from the names of everyday objects and animals.  The same surname could also refer to a [[Gauls|Gaul]], indicating someone of Gaulish descent, or whose appearance or character resembled that of a Gaul.<ref>Chase, pp. 112\u2013114.</ref><ref>''New College Latin & English Dictionary'', ''s. v. gallus''.</ref>\n\n==Members==\n{{Filiation}}\n\n* Sextus Didius, the grandfather of Titus Didius, the consul of 98 BC.\n* Titus Didius Sex. f., [[Tribune of the Plebs|tribune of the plebs]] in 143 BC, was probably the author of the [[sumptuary law]], ''lex Didia'', which was binding on all of Italy, in contrast with the ''lex Fannia'' of 161, which had no power except in the city of Rome.  He is probably the same Titus Didius who was sent as [[praetor]] against the revolted slaves in [[Sicily]], about 138.<ref>Macrobius, ''Saturnalia'', ii. 13.</ref>\n* Gaius Didius C. f., a senator in 129 BC.<ref>Sherk, \"''Senatus Consultum De Agro Pergameno''\", p. 368.</ref>\n* [[Titus Didius|Titus Didius T. f. Sex. n.]], as praetor in 100 BC, triumphed over the [[Scordisci]]; [[Roman consul|consul]] in 98, he and his colleague passed the ''[[lex Caecilia Didia]]''.  Afterwards [[proconsul]] in [[Hispania|Spain]], he triumphed over the [[Celtiberians]].  Didius fell during the [[Social War (91\u201388 BC)|Social War]], in the spring of 89.<ref>Florus, iii. 4.</ref><ref>Ammianus Marcellinus, xxvii. 4.</ref><ref>Cicero, ''In Pisonem'', 25, ''De Domo Sua'', 16, 20, ''Pro Sestio'', 64, ''Philippicae'', v. 3, ''Pro Plancio'', 25.</ref><ref>Eusebius, ''Chronicon'', clxx. 2.</ref><ref>Scholia Bobiensia, ''In Ciceronis Pro Sestio'', p. 310.</ref><ref>''[[Fasti Triumphales]]'', {{AE|1889|70}}; 1893, 80; 1904, 113, 196; 1930, 60; 1940, 61.</ref><ref>Appian, ''Hispanica'', 99 ''ff'', ''Bellum Civile'', i. 40.</ref><ref>Sallust, ''apud'' Gellius, ii. 27.</ref><ref>Velleius Paterculus, ii. 16.</ref><ref>Ovid, ''Fasti'', vi. 567 ''ff''.</ref><ref>''Dictionary of Greek and Roman Biography and Mythology'', vol. I, pp. 1004, 1005 (\"Didius\", No. 2).</ref>\n* Titus Didius (T. f. T. n.), ''[[List of Roman moneyers during the Republic|triumvir monetalis]]'' in 113 or 112 BC, and tribune of the plebs in 95.  He and his colleague, Lucius Aurelius Cotta, were forced from the tribunal hearing the disputes arising from the accusation brought against [[Quintus Servilius Caepio the Younger|Caepio]].<ref>Cicero, ''De Oratore'', ii. 47.</ref>\n* Gaius Didius, [[legatus|legate]] of [[Julius Caesar|Caesar]] in 46 BC, was sent against [[Pompey|Gnaeus Pompeius]], winning a naval victory over Quintus Attius Varus.  Didius pursued Pompeius, capturing or destroying his ships.  After the death of Pompeius, Didius was attacked and slain by his quarry's [[Lusitania]]n soldiers.<ref>Cassius Dio, ''Roman History'', xliii. 14, 31, 40.</ref><ref>Caesar, ''De Bello Hispaniensis'', 37, 40.</ref>\n* [[Quintus Didius]], governor of [[Syria (Roman province)|Syria]] in 31 BC.  Although probably appointed by [[Mark Antony|Marcus Antonius]], he went over to [[Augustus|Octavian]] after the [[Battle of Actium]], and persuaded the Arabs to burn a fleet that Antonius had built in the [[Red Sea]].<ref>Cassius Dio, ''Roman History'', li. 7.</ref>\n* [[Aulus Didius Gallus]], superintendent of aqueducts during the reign of [[Caligula]], AD 40; under [[Claudius]], commanded a Roman army in [[Bosporan Kingdom|Bosporus]], AD 50, and subsequently appointed to succeed [[Publius Ostorius Scapula]] as governor of [[Roman Britain|Britain]].\n* [[Aulus Didius Gallus Fabricius Veiento]], praetor during the reign of [[Nero]], he was banished for publishing a number of libels, and for supposedly selling the honours granted by the emperor.  He subsequently returned to Rome, and was consul at least twice, the second time under [[Titus]] in AD 80.  [[Aurelius Victor]] reports that he was a favourite of [[Domitian]], under whom he was consul.<ref>Gallivan, \"The ''Fasti'' for A.D. 70\u201396\", pp. 189, 197, 215.</ref>\n* Didius Scaeva, one of the generals of [[Vitellius]], who was slain at the taking of the Capitol in AD 69.\n* Titus Didius Secundus, consul ''suffectus'' under [[Trajan]] in AD 102.<ref>{{AE|2013|650}}.</ref>\n* Lucius Didius Marinus, the second husband of [[Annia Cornificia Faustina Minor]], daughter of the [[Roman emperor|emperor]] [[Marcus Aurelius]].\n* [[Quintus Petronius Didius Severus|Quintus Petronius Didius Q. f. Severus]], father of the emperor Didius Julianus.\n* [[Didius Julianus|Marcus Didius Q. f. Q. n. Salvius Julianus]], afterwards Marcus Didius Commodus Severus Julianus, consul in AD 175 and 179, and [[Roman emperor]] for nine weeks in AD 193.\n* Didius Q. f. Q. n. Proculus, brother of the emperor Didius Julianus.\n* Didius Q. f. Q. n. Nummius Albinus, brother of the emperor Didius Julianus.\n* [[Didia Clara|Didia M. f. Q. n. Clara]], daughter and only child of [[Didius Julianus]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Roman gentes]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* [[Cicero|Marcus Tullius Cicero]], ''De Domo Sua'', ''[[De Oratore]]'', ''In Pisonem'', ''[[Philippicae]]'', ''Pro Murena'', ''Pro Plancio'', ''Pro Sestio''.\n* [[Julius Caesar|Gaius Julius Caesar]], ''De Bello Hispaniensis'' (On the War in Spain, attributed).\n* Publius Ovidius Naso ([[Ovid]]), ''[[Fasti (poem)|Fasti]]''.\n* [[Marcus Velleius Paterculus]], ''Compendium of Roman History''.\n* [[Florus|Lucius Annaeus Florus]], ''Epitome de T. Livio Bellorum Omnium Annorum DCC'' (Epitome of Livy: All the Wars of Seven Hundred Years).\n* Appianus Alexandrinus ([[Appian]]), ''Hispanica'' (The Spanish Wars), ''Bellum Civile'' (The Civil War).\n* [[Aulus Gellius]], ''Noctes Atticae'' (Attic Nights).\n* Lucius Cassius Dio Cocceianus ([[Cassius Dio]]), ''Roman History''.\n* [[Eusebius of Caesarea]], ''[[Chronicon (Eusebius)|Chronicon]]''.\n* [[Ammianus Marcellinus]], ''Res Gestae''.\n* [[Macrobius|Ambrosius Theodosius Macrobius]], ''Saturnalia''.\n* Scholia Bobiensia ([[Bobbio Scholiast]]), ''In Ciceronis Pro Sestio'' (Commentary on Cicero\u2019s Oration ''Pro Sestio'').\n* ''[[Dictionary of Greek and Roman Biography and Mythology]]'', [[William Smith (lexicographer)|William Smith]], ed., Little, Brown and Company, Boston (1849).\n* Ren\u00e9 Cagnat ''et alii'', ''[[L'Ann\u00e9e \u00e9pigraphique]]'' (The Year in Epigraphy, abbreviated ''AE''), Presses Universitaires de France (1888\u2013present).\n* George Davis Chase, \"The Origin of Roman Praenomina\", in ''Harvard Studies in Classical Philology'', vol. VIII, pp. 103\u2013184 (1897).\n* Robert K. Sherk, \"[http://grbs.library.duke.edu/article/viewFile/11381/4167 The Text of the ''Senatus Consultum De Agro Pergameno'']\", in ''Greek, Roman, and Byzantine Studies'', vol. 7, pp. 361\u2013369 (1966).\n*[[Michael Crawford (historian)|Michael Crawford]], ''Roman Republican Coinage'', Cambridge University Press (1974, 2001).\n*Paul A. Gallivan, \"The ''Fasti'' for A.D. 70\u201396\", in ''[[Classical Quarterly]]'', vol. 31, pp. 186\u2013220 (1981).\n* John C. Traupman, ''The New College Latin & English Dictionary'', Bantam Books, New York (1995).\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Didia (gens)}}\n[[Category:Didii| ]]\n[[Category:Roman gentes]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:T._Didius,_denarius,_113-112_BC,_RRC_294-1.jpg|thumb|300x300px|[[Denarius]] of [[Titus Didius]], minted in 113 or 112 BC. [[Roma (mythology)|Roma]] is portrayed on the obverse, while the reverse depicts two [[Gladiator|gladiators]]. It may represent a political promise from Didius to offer gladiatorial shows, should he be elected [[Aedile|curule aedile]].<ref>Crawford, ''Roman Republican Coinage'', p. 308.</ref>]]\nThe '''gens Didia''', or '''Deidia''', as the name is spelled on coins, was a [[plebs|plebeian]] family at [[Ancient Rome]], which first appears in history during the final century of the [[Roman Republic|Republic]].  According to [[Cicero]], they were ''[[novus homo|novi homines]]''.  [[Titus Didius]] obtained the [[Roman consul|consulship]] in 98 BC, a dignity shared by no other Didii until [[Roman Empire|imperial times]].<ref name=\"DGRBM\">''Dictionary of Greek and Roman Biography and Mythology'', vol. I, p. 1004 (\"Didia Gens\").</ref><ref>Cicero, ''Pro Murena'', 8.</ref>\n\n==Origin==\nThe [[Roman naming conventions#Nomen|nomen]] ''Didius'' or ''Deidius'' is of uncertain origin.  It resembles a class of gentilicia formed from [[cognomen|cognomina]] ending in ''-idus'', but might be derived from a cognomen ''Dida''.  Chase classifies it among those gentilicia that either originated at Rome, or cannot be shown to have come from anywhere else.<ref>Chase, pp. 121, 122, 130.</ref>\n\n==Praenomina==\nThe earlier Didii used the [[praenomen|praenomina]] ''[[Sextus (praenomen)|Sextus]]'', ''[[Titus (praenomen)|Titus]]'', and ''[[Gaius (praenomen)|Gaius]]'', to which later members of the family added ''[[Quintus (praenomen)|Quintus]]'', ''[[Aulus (praenomen)|Aulus]]'', and ''[[Lucius (praenomen)|Lucius]]''.  All of these were common throughout Roman history.\n\n==Branches and cognomina==\nNone of the Didii mentioned during the Republic is known to have borne a cognomen.<ref name=\"DGRBM\"/>  A number of surnames are found under the Empire, of which the only one that appears to be a family name is ''Gallus''.  This cognomen, referring to a cockerel, belongs to an abundant class of cognomina derived from the names of everyday objects and animals.  The same surname could also refer to a [[Gauls|Gaul]], indicating someone of Gaulish descent, or whose appearance or character resembled that of a Gaul.<ref>Chase, pp. 112\u2013114.</ref><ref>''New College Latin & English Dictionary'', ''s. v. gallus''.</ref>\n\n==Members==\n{{Filiation}}\n\n* Sextus Didius, the grandfather of Titus Didius, the consul of 98 BC.\n* Titus Didius Sex. f., [[Tribune of the Plebs|tribune of the plebs]] in 143 BC, was probably the author of the [[sumptuary law]], ''lex Didia'', which was binding on all of Italy, in contrast with the ''lex Fannia'' of 161, which had no power except in the city of Rome.  He is probably the same Titus Didius who was sent as [[praetor]] against the revolted slaves in [[Sicily]], about 138.<ref>Macrobius, ''Saturnalia'', ii. 13.</ref>\n* Gaius Didius C. f., a senator in 129 BC.<ref>Sherk, \"''Senatus Consultum De Agro Pergameno''\", p. 368.</ref>\n* [[Titus Didius|Titus Didius T. f. Sex. n.]], as praetor in 100 BC, triumphed over the [[Scordisci]]; [[Roman consul|consul]] in 98, he and his colleague passed the ''[[lex Caecilia Didia]]''.  Afterwards [[proconsul]] in [[Hispania|Spain]], he triumphed over the [[Celtiberians]].  Didius fell during the [[Social War (91\u201388 BC)|Social War]], in the spring of 89.<ref>Florus, iii. 4.</ref><ref>Ammianus Marcellinus, xxvii. 4.</ref><ref>Cicero, ''In Pisonem'', 25, ''De Domo Sua'', 16, 20, ''Pro Sestio'', 64, ''Philippicae'', v. 3, ''Pro Plancio'', 25.</ref><ref>Eusebius, ''Chronicon'', clxx. 2.</ref><ref>Scholia Bobiensia, ''In Ciceronis Pro Sestio'', p. 310.</ref><ref>''[[Fasti Triumphales]]'', {{AE|1889|70}}; 1893, 80; 1904, 113, 196; 1930, 60; 1940, 61.</ref><ref>Appian, ''Hispanica'', 99 ''ff'', ''Bellum Civile'', i. 40.</ref><ref>Sallust, ''apud'' Gellius, ii. 27.</ref><ref>Velleius Paterculus, ii. 16.</ref><ref>Ovid, ''Fasti'', vi. 567 ''ff''.</ref><ref>''Dictionary of Greek and Roman Biography and Mythology'', vol. I, pp. 1004, 1005 (\"Didius\", No. 2).</ref>\n* Titus Didius (T. f. T. n.), ''[[List of Roman moneyers during the Republic|triumvir monetalis]]'' in 113 or 112 BC, and tribune of the plebs in 95.  He and his colleague, Lucius Aurelius Cotta, were forced from the tribunal hearing the disputes arising from the accusation brought against [[Quintus Servilius Caepio the Younger|Caepio]].<ref>Cicero, ''De Oratore'', ii. 47.</ref>\n* Gaius Didius, [[legatus|legate]] of [[Julius Caesar|Caesar]] in 46 BC, was sent against [[Pompey|Gnaeus Pompeius]], winning a naval victory over Quintus Attius Varus.  Didius pursued Pompeius, capturing or destroying his ships.  After the death of Pompeius, Didius was attacked and slain by his quarry's [[Lusitania]]n soldiers.<ref>Cassius Dio, ''Roman History'', xliii. 14, 31, 40.</ref><ref>Caesar, ''De Bello Hispaniensis'', 37, 40.</ref>\n* [[Quintus Didius]], governor of [[Syria (Roman province)|Syria]] in 31 BC.  Although probably appointed by [[Mark Antony|Marcus Antonius]], he went over to [[Augustus|Octavian]] after the [[Battle of Actium]], and persuaded the Arabs to burn a fleet that Antonius had built in the [[Red Sea]].<ref>Cassius Dio, ''Roman History'', li. 7.</ref>\n* [[Aulus Didius Gallus]], superintendent of aqueducts during the reign of [[Caligula]], AD 40; under [[Claudius]], commanded a Roman army in [[Bosporan Kingdom|Bosporus]], AD 50, and subsequently appointed to succeed [[Publius Ostorius Scapula]] as governor of [[Roman Britain|Britain]].\n* [[Aulus Didius Gallus Fabricius Veiento]], praetor during the reign of [[Nero]], he was banished for publishing a number of libels, and for supposedly selling the honours granted by the emperor.  He subsequently returned to Rome, and was consul at least twice, the second time under [[Titus]] in AD 80.  [[Aurelius Victor]] reports that he was a favourite of [[Domitian]], under whom he was consul.<ref>Gallivan, \"The ''Fasti'' for A.D. 70\u201396\", pp. 189, 197, 215.</ref>\n* Didius Scaeva, one of the generals of [[Vitellius]], who was slain at the taking of the Capitol in AD 69.\n* Titus Didius Secundus, consul ''suffectus'' under [[Trajan]] in AD 102.<ref>{{AE|2013|650}}.</ref>\n* Lucius Didius Marinus, the second husband of [[Annia Cornificia Faustina Minor]], daughter of the [[Roman emperor|emperor]] [[Marcus Aurelius]].\n* [[Quintus Petronius Didius Severus|Quintus Petronius Didius Q. f. Severus]], father of the emperor Didius Julianus.\n* [[Didius Julianus|Marcus Didius Q. f. Q. n. Salvius Julianus]], afterwards Marcus Didius Commodus Severus Julianus, consul in AD 175 and 179, and [[Roman emperor]] for nine weeks in AD 193.\n* Didius Q. f. Q. n. Proculus, brother of the emperor Didius Julianus.\n* Didius Q. f. Q. n. Nummius Albinus, brother of the emperor Didius Julianus.\n* [[Didia Clara|Didia Q. f. Q. n. Clara]], daughter and only child of [[Didius Julianus]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Roman gentes]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* [[Cicero|Marcus Tullius Cicero]], ''De Domo Sua'', ''[[De Oratore]]'', ''In Pisonem'', ''[[Philippicae]]'', ''Pro Murena'', ''Pro Plancio'', ''Pro Sestio''.\n* [[Julius Caesar|Gaius Julius Caesar]], ''De Bello Hispaniensis'' (On the War in Spain, attributed).\n* Publius Ovidius Naso ([[Ovid]]), ''[[Fasti (poem)|Fasti]]''.\n* [[Marcus Velleius Paterculus]], ''Compendium of Roman History''.\n* [[Florus|Lucius Annaeus Florus]], ''Epitome de T. Livio Bellorum Omnium Annorum DCC'' (Epitome of Livy: All the Wars of Seven Hundred Years).\n* Appianus Alexandrinus ([[Appian]]), ''Hispanica'' (The Spanish Wars), ''Bellum Civile'' (The Civil War).\n* [[Aulus Gellius]], ''Noctes Atticae'' (Attic Nights).\n* Lucius Cassius Dio Cocceianus ([[Cassius Dio]]), ''Roman History''.\n* [[Eusebius of Caesarea]], ''[[Chronicon (Eusebius)|Chronicon]]''.\n* [[Ammianus Marcellinus]], ''Res Gestae''.\n* [[Macrobius|Ambrosius Theodosius Macrobius]], ''Saturnalia''.\n* Scholia Bobiensia ([[Bobbio Scholiast]]), ''In Ciceronis Pro Sestio'' (Commentary on Cicero\u2019s Oration ''Pro Sestio'').\n* ''[[Dictionary of Greek and Roman Biography and Mythology]]'', [[William Smith (lexicographer)|William Smith]], ed., Little, Brown and Company, Boston (1849).\n* Ren\u00e9 Cagnat ''et alii'', ''[[L'Ann\u00e9e \u00e9pigraphique]]'' (The Year in Epigraphy, abbreviated ''AE''), Presses Universitaires de France (1888\u2013present).\n* George Davis Chase, \"The Origin of Roman Praenomina\", in ''Harvard Studies in Classical Philology'', vol. VIII, pp. 103\u2013184 (1897).\n* Robert K. Sherk, \"[http://grbs.library.duke.edu/article/viewFile/11381/4167 The Text of the ''Senatus Consultum De Agro Pergameno'']\", in ''Greek, Roman, and Byzantine Studies'', vol. 7, pp. 361\u2013369 (1966).\n*[[Michael Crawford (historian)|Michael Crawford]], ''Roman Republican Coinage'', Cambridge University Press (1974, 2001).\n*Paul A. Gallivan, \"The ''Fasti'' for A.D. 70\u201396\", in ''[[Classical Quarterly]]'', vol. 31, pp. 186\u2013220 (1981).\n* John C. Traupman, ''The New College Latin & English Dictionary'', Bantam Books, New York (1995).\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Didia (gens)}}\n[[Category:Didii| ]]\n[[Category:Roman gentes]]\n", "name_user": "P Aculeius", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMembers:If her father was Marcus, she was M. f., not Q. f.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Didia_(gens)"}
{"title_page": "Waldorf Stakes", "text_new": "{{Infobox horseraces\n| class         = Discontinued stakes\n| horse race    = Waldorf Stakes\n| website\n| image         = \n| caption       = \n| location      = [[Sheepshead Bay Race Track]]<br>[[Sheepshead Bay, Brooklyn|Sheepshead Bay]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| inaugurated   = 1904\n| race type     = [[Thoroughbred]] - [[Flat racing]]\n| distance      = 6 [[Furlong]]s\n| surface       = Dirt\n| track         = left-handed\n| qualification = Two-year-old colts & geldings\n| weight        = \n| purse         = \n| bonuses       = \n}}\n\nThe '''Waldorf Stakes''' was an American [[Thoroughbred racing|Thoroughbred horse race]] held annually at [[Sheepshead Bay Race Track]] in [[Sheepshead Bay, Brooklyn|Sheepshead Bay]], [[New York (state)|New York]]. Open to two-year-old [[Colt (horse)|colts]] and [[gelding]]s, it was run on dirt over a distance of six [[furlong]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://drf.uky.edu/catalog/1900s/drf1907091101/drf1907091101_3_3 |title=Condensed History of the Waldorf Stakes |publisher=Daily Racing Form at University of Kentucky Archives |date=1907-09-11 |accessdate=2019-08-18}}</ref> First run in 1904, the ''[[Daily Racing Form]]'' reported that \"The owner of the winner gives an elaborate dinner to the other subscribers to the event and its winning is an honor keenly coveted.\" However, the race had a very short tenure after passage of the [[Hart-Agnew Law|Hart-Agnew]] anti-betting legislation by the [[New York Legislature]] which devastated horse racing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://drf.uky.edu/catalog/1900s/drf1908011801/drf1908011801_1_7 |title=Penalties in the New York Bills |publisher=Daily Racing Form at University of Kentucky Archives |date=1908-01-18|accessdate=2018-10-26}}</ref> The winner's share of the purse for the Waldorf Stakes was always in the area of $6,000 but for what would prove to be its last running, the winner's share for 1908 was reduced by more than 70%.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://drf.uky.edu/catalog/1900s/drf1908091001/drf1908091001_3_1 |title=New York Form Chart |publisher=Daily Racing Form at University of Kentucky Archives |date=1908-09-10|accessdate=2019-08-18}}</ref> When a February 21, 1913 ruling by the [[New York Supreme Court, Appellate Division]] saw horse racing return it was too late for the Sheepshead Bay horse racing facility and it never reopened.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://drf.uky.edu/catalog/1910s/drf1913022201/drf1913022201_1_9 |title= Oral Betting Held Legal: Appellate Division of New York Supreme Court Renders Important Decision |publisher=Daily Racing Form at University of Kentucky Archives |date=1913-02-22 |accessdate=2019-06-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://drf.uky.edu/catalog/1900s/drf1908121501/drf1908121501_1_7|title=Destruction Wrought by Hughes |publisher=Daily Racing Form at University of Kentucky Archives |date=1908-12-15|accessdate=2018-11-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://drf.uky.edu/catalog/1910s/drf1914111701/drf1914111701_1_2 |title=Famous Old Track is Sold |publisher=Daily Racing Form at University of Kentucky Archives |date=1914-11-17|accessdate=2018-11-30}}</ref>\n\n==Historical notes==\nThe inaugural running of the Waldorf Stakes took place on September 7, 1904. It was won by [[Agile (horse)|Agile]], a colt owned by prominent [[Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania|Pittsburgh]] businessman [[Samuel S. Brown|Samuel Brown]]. Agile would go on to win the 1905 [[Tennessee Derby|Tennessee]]  and [[Kentucky Derby]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1904/09/08/issue.html |title=Beldame Won In A Romp |publisher=New York Times, page 8 |date=1904-09-08 |accessdate=2020-02-01}}</ref>\n\nThe 1906 Waldorf Stakes was won by Kentucky Beau in what would turn out to be the event's fastest time. Kentucky Beau was ridden by [[African Americans|African American]] jockey Leroy Williams and trained by African American [[French Brooks]] for [[Runnymede Farm|Runnymede Farm's]] [[Woodford Clay]] of the renowned [[Clay family]] of Kentucky.\n\nThe final running on September 9, 1908 was the second consecutive win for the [[Oneck Stable]]. Their colt Ben Fleet had won it in 1907 and [[Fashion Plate (horse)|Fashion Plate]] in this final year. Fashion Plate have a stellar career in racing with wins in the [[Brookdale Handicap|Brookdale]], [[Edgemere Handicap|Edgemere]], [[Long Island Handicap|Long Island]] and prestigious [[Metropolitan Handicap]], among others.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://drf.uky.edu/catalog/1900s/drf1908091001/drf1908091001_3_1 |title=New York Form Chart |publisher=Daily Racing Form at University of Kentucky Archives |date=1908-09-10|accessdate=2019-08-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://drf.uky.edu/catalog/ |title=Fashion Plate Wins Metropolitan |publisher=New York Times,  page 11 |date=1910-05-14 |accessdate=2020-02-01}}</ref>\n\n==Records==\n'''Speed record:'''\n* 1:13 1/5 @ 6 [[furlong]]s : Kentucky Beau (1906)\n\n'''Most wins:'''\n* No horse won this race more than once.\n\n'''Most wins by a [[jockey]]:'''\n* No jockey won this race more than once.\n\n'''Most wins by a [[Horse trainer|trainer]]:'''\n* 2 - [[William H. Karrick]] (1907, 1908)\n\n'''Most wins by an owner:'''\n* 2 [[Harry K. Knapp#Oneck Stable|Oneck Stable]] (1907, 1908)\n\n==Winners==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:90%\"\n|- \n! style=\"width:25px\" | Year<br>\n! style=\"width:110px\" | Winner<br>\n! style=\"width:20px\" | Age<br>\n! style=\"width:110px\" | Jockey<br>\n! style=\"width:120px\" | Trainer<br>\n! Owner<br>\n! style=\"width:25px\" | Dist.<br> <span style=\"font-size:70%\">([[Mile]]s)</span>\n! style=\"width:25px\" | Time<br>\n! style=\"width:25px\" | Win<br>[[United States dollar|$]]\n|-\n|align=center|1908\n|[[Fashion Plate (horse)|Fashion Plate]]\n|align=center|2\n|James Butler Jr.\n|[[William H. Karrick]]\n|[[Harry K. Knapp#Oneck Stable|Oneck Stable]]\n|align=center|6 F\n|1:13.40\n|$1,625\n|-\n|align=center|1907\n|Ben Fleet\n|align=center|2\n|[[Dave Nicol]]\n|William H. Karrick\n|Oneck Stable\n|align=center|6 F\n|1:15.20\n|$5,510\n|-\n|align=center|1906\n|Kentucky Beau\n|align=center|2\n|Leroy Williams\n|[[French Brooks]]\n|[[Woodford Clay]]\n|align=center|6 F\n|1:13.20\n|$5,875\n|-\n|align=center|1905\n|Vendor\n|align=center|2\n|[[Lucien Lyne]]\n|William H. Brooks\n|[[Francis R. Hitchcock]]\n|align=center|6 F\n|1:14.40\n|$6,375\n|-\n|align=center|1904\n|[[Agile (horse)|Agile]] \n|align=center|2\n|[[Thomas H. Burns|Tommy Burns]]\n|[[Robert Tucker (horse trainer)|Robert Tucker]]\n|[[Samuel S. Brown]]\n|align=center|6 F\n|1:13.40\n|$6,000\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Discontinued horse races]]\n[[Category:Horse races in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Flat horse races for two-year-olds]]\n[[Category:Open sprint category horse races]]\n[[Category:Sheepshead Bay Race Track]]\n[[Category:Recurring sporting events established in 1904]]\n[[Category:Recurring sporting events disestablished in 1908]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox horseraces\n| class         = Discontinued stakes\n| horse race    = Waldorf Stakes\n| website\n| image         = \n| caption       = \n| location      = [[Sheepshead Bay Race Track]]<br>[[Sheepshead Bay, Brooklyn|Sheepshead Bay]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| inaugurated   = 1904\n| race type     = [[Thoroughbred]] - [[Flat racing]]\n| distance      = 6 [[Furlong|Furlongs]]\n| surface       = Dirt\n| track         = left-handed\n| qualification = Two-year-old colts & geldings\n| weight        = \n| purse         = \n| bonuses       = \n}}\n\nThe '''Waldorf Stakes''' was an American [[Thoroughbred racing|Thoroughbred horse race]] held annually at [[Sheepshead Bay Race Track]] in [[Sheepshead Bay, Brooklyn|Sheepshead Bay]], [[New York (state)|New York]]. Open to two-year-old [[Colt (horse)|colts]] and [[gelding]]s, it was run on dirt over a distance of six [[Furlong|furlongs]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://drf.uky.edu/catalog/1900s/drf1907091101/drf1907091101_3_3 |title=Condensed History of the Waldorf Stakes |publisher=Daily Racing Form at University of Kentucky Archives |date=1907-09-11 |accessdate=2019-08-18}}</ref> First run in 1904, the ''[[Daily Racing Form]]'' reported that \"The owner of the winner gives an elaborate dinner to the other subscribers to the event and its winning is an honor keenly coveted.\" However, the race had a very short tenure after passage of the [[Hart-Agnew Law|Hart-Agnew]] anti-betting legislation by the [[New York Legislature]] which devastated horse racing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://drf.uky.edu/catalog/1900s/drf1908011801/drf1908011801_1_7 |title=Penalties in the New York Bills |publisher=Daily Racing Form at University of Kentucky Archives |date=1908-01-18|accessdate=2018-10-26}}</ref> The winner's share of the purse for the Waldorf Stakes was always in the area of $6,000 but for what would prove to be its last running, the winner's share for 1908 was reduced by more than 70%.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://drf.uky.edu/catalog/1900s/drf1908091001/drf1908091001_3_1 |title=New York Form Chart |publisher=Daily Racing Form at University of Kentucky Archives |date=1908-09-10|accessdate=2019-08-18}}</ref> When a February 21, 1913 ruling by the [[New York Supreme Court, Appellate Division]] saw horse racing return it was too late for the Sheepshead Bay horse racing facility and it never reopened.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://drf.uky.edu/catalog/1910s/drf1913022201/drf1913022201_1_9 |title= Oral Betting Held Legal: Appellate Division of New York Supreme Court Renders Important Decision |publisher=Daily Racing Form at University of Kentucky Archives |date=1913-02-22 |accessdate=2019-06-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://drf.uky.edu/catalog/1900s/drf1908121501/drf1908121501_1_7|title=Destruction Wrought by Hughes |publisher=Daily Racing Form at University of Kentucky Archives |date=1908-12-15|accessdate=2018-11-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://drf.uky.edu/catalog/1910s/drf1914111701/drf1914111701_1_2 |title=Famous Old Track is Sold |publisher=Daily Racing Form at University of Kentucky Archives |date=1914-11-17|accessdate=2018-11-30}}</ref>\n\n==Historical notes==\nThe inaugural running of the Waldorf Stakes took place on September 7, 1904. It was won by [[Agile (horse)|Agile]], a colt owned by prominent [[Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania|Pittsburgh]] businessman [[Samuel S. Brown|Samuel Brown]]. Agile would go on to win the 1905 [[Tennesse Derby|Tennessee]]  and [[Kentucky Derby]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1904/09/08/issue.html |title=Beldame Won In A Romp |publisher=New York Times, page 8 |date=1904-09-08 |accessdate=2020-02-01}}</ref>\n\nThe 1906 Waldorf Stakes was won by Kentucky Beau in what would turn out to be the event's fastest time. Kentucky Beau was ridden by [[African Americans|African American]] jockey Leroy Williams and trained by African American [[French Brooks]] for [[Runnymede Farm|Runnymede Farm's]] [[Woodford Clay]] of the renowned [[Clay family]] of Kentucky.\n\nThe final running on September 9, 1908 was the second consecutive win for the [[Oneck Stable]]. Their colt Ben Fleet had won it in 1907 and [[Fashion Plate (horse)|Fashion Plate]] in this final year. Fashion Plate have a stellar career in racing with wins in the [[Brookdale Handicap|Brookdale]], [[Edgemere Handicap|Edgemere]], [[Long Island Handicap|Long Island]] and prestigious [[Metropolitan Handicap]], among others.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://drf.uky.edu/catalog/1900s/drf1908091001/drf1908091001_3_1 |title=New York Form Chart |publisher=Daily Racing Form at University of Kentucky Archives |date=1908-09-10|accessdate=2019-08-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://drf.uky.edu/catalog/ |title=Fashion Plate Wins Metropolitan |publisher=New York Times,  page 11 |date=1910-05-14 |accessdate=2020-02-01}}</ref>\n\n==Records==\n'''Speed record:'''\n* 1:13 1/5 @ 6 [[Furlong|furlongs]] : Kentucky Beau (1906)\n\n'''Most wins:'''\n* No horse won this race more than once.\n\n'''Most wins by a [[jockey]]:'''\n* No jockey won this race more than once.\n\n'''Most wins by a [[Horse trainer|trainer]]:'''\n* 2 - [[William H. Karrick]] (1907, 1908)\n\n'''Most wins by an owner:'''\n* 2 [[Harry K. Knapp#Oneck Stable|Oneck Stable]] (1907, 1908)\n\n==Winners==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:90%\"\n|- \n! style=\"width:25px\" | Year<br>\n! style=\"width:110px\" | Winner<br>\n! style=\"width:20px\" | Age<br>\n! style=\"width:110px\" | Jockey<br>\n! style=\"width:120px\" | Trainer<br>\n! Owner<br>\n! style=\"width:25px\" | Dist.<br> <span style=\"font-size:70%\">([[Mile|Miles]])</span>\n! style=\"width:25px\" | Time<br>\n! style=\"width:25px\" | Win<br>[[United States dollar|$]]\n|-\n|align=center|1908\n|[[Fashion Plate (horse)|Fashion Plate]]\n|align=center|2\n|James Butler Jr.\n|[[William H. Karrick]]\n|[[Harry K. Knapp#Oneck Stable|Oneck Stable]]\n|align=center|6 F\n|1:13.40\n|$1,625\n|-\n|align=center|1907\n|Ben Fleet\n|align=center|2\n|[[Dave Nicol]]\n|William H. Karrick\n|Oneck Stable\n|align=center|6 F\n|1:15.20\n|$5,510\n|-\n|align=center|1906\n|Kentucky Beau\n|align=center|2\n|Leroy Williams\n|[[French Brooks]]\n|[[Woodford Clay]]\n|align=center|6 F\n|1:13.20\n|$5,875\n|-\n|align=center|1905\n|Vendor\n|align=center|2\n|[[Lucien Lyne]]\n|William H. Brooks\n|[[Francis R. Hitchcock]]\n|align=center|6 F\n|1:14.40\n|$6,375\n|-\n|align=center|1904\n|[[Agile (horse)|Agile]] \n|align=center|2\n|[[Thomas H. Burns|Tommy Burns]]\n|[[Robert Tucker (horse trainer)|Robert Tucker]]\n|[[Samuel S. Brown]]\n|align=center|6 F\n|1:13.40\n|$6,000\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Discontinued horse races]]\n[[Category:Horse races in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Flat horse races for two-year-olds]]\n[[Category:Open sprint category horse races]]\n[[Category:Sheepshead Bay Race Track]]\n[[Category:Recurring sporting events established in 1904]]\n[[Category:Recurring sporting events disestablished in 1908]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo/generalfixes, replaced: Tennesse \u2192 Tennessee", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Waldorf_Stakes"}
{"title_page": "List of ships of the Bangladesh Coast Guard", "text_new": "[[File:\u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b6 \u0995\u09cb\u09b8\u09cd\u099f \u0997\u09be\u09b0\u09cd\u09a1\u09c7\u09b0 \u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09a4\u09c0\u0995.svg|thumbnail|150px|Monogram of [[Bangladesh Coast Guard]].]]\n[[Bangladesh Coast Guard]] currently operates 47 surface ships and craft. Most of them are small coastal patrol vessels. The coast guard ships use the prefix \"CGS\" before the name of the ships which stands for \"Coast Guard  Ship\".\n\n==Offshore patrol vessels==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"color:#fff; background:#079; width:15%;\"|Class\n! style=\"color:#fff; background:#079; width:10%;\"|Picture\n! style=\"color:#fff; background:#079; width:11%;\"|Type\n! style=\"color:#fff; background:#079; width:20%;\"|Ships\n! style=\"color:#fff; background:#079; width:10%;\"|Origin\n! style=\"color:#fff; background:#079; width:6%;\"|Displacement (Tons)\n! style=\"color:#fff; background:#079; width:28%;\"|Note\n|-\n! colspan=\"7\" style=\"background: lavender;\"| Active (2)\n|-\n|[[Minerva-class corvette#Leader Class OPV|Leader Class OPV]]||[[File:Coast Guard Ship (Bangladesh).jpg|200px]]|| [[Patrol boat#Classification|Offshore Patrol Vessel]] || [[CGS Syed Nazrul]] (PL 71) <br> [[CGS Tajuddin]] (PL 72) || {{ITA}} || {{align|center|1 285}} || ''Minerva'' and ''Sibilla'' were refitted at [[Fincantieri]]. Delivery was completed on 3 August 2016.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.theindependentbd.com/post/54360| title=Italian navy hands over two warships to Coast Guard| publisher=[[The Independent (Bangladesh newspaper)|The Independent]]| date=4 August 2016| accessdate=4 November 2016| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161104205734/http://www.theindependentbd.com/post/54360#| archive-date=2016-11-04| url-status=live}}</ref> Two ships arrived in [[Port of Chittagong|Chittagong]] on 2 November 2016.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.janes.com/article/65289/new-opv-deliveries-see-bangladesh-s-coastguard-continue-to-expand| title=New OPV deliveries see Bangladesh's coastguard continue to expand| publisher=[[IHS Jane's]]| date=4 November 2016| accessdate=4 November 2016| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161105033015/http://www.janes.com/article/65289/new-opv-deliveries-see-bangladesh-s-coastguard-continue-to-expand#| archive-date=2016-11-05| url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Minerva-class corvette#Leader Class OPV|Leader Class OPV]]||[[File:Coast Guard Ship (Bangladesh).jpg|200px]]|| [[Patrol boat#Classification|Offshore Patrol Vessel]] || [[CGS Mansoor Ali]] (PL 73) <br> [[CGS Kamaruzzaman]] (PL 74)  || {{ITA}} || {{align|center|1 285}} || ''Urania'' and ''Danaide'' were delivered after refitting on 12 October 2017<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.defnat.com/e-RDN/vue-tribune.php?ctribune=1031 |title=Une nouvelle vie pour deux anciennes corvettes italiennes, un exemple \u00e0 suivre |date=11 November 2017 |website=Revue D\u00e9fense nationale |language=fr }}</ref> and arrived in [[Port of Mongla|Mongla]] on 22 December 2017.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.thedailystar.net/city/2-patrol-vessels-join-coast-guard-fleet-today-1508605| title=2 patrol vessels join Coast Guard fleet| publisher=[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|The Daily Star]]| date=22 December 2017| accessdate=23 December 2017| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171223172551/http://www.thedailystar.net/city/2-patrol-vessels-join-coast-guard-fleet-today-1508605#| archive-date=2017-12-23| url-status=live}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Inshore patrol vessels==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"color:#fff; background:#079; width:15%;\"|Class\n! style=\"color:#fff; background:#079; width:10%;\"|Picture\n! style=\"color:#fff; background:#079; width:12%;\"|Type\n! style=\"color:#fff; background:#079; width:17%;\"|Ships\n! style=\"color:#fff; background:#079; width:12%;\"|Origin\n! style=\"color:#fff; background:#079; width:6%;\"|Displacement (Tons)\n! style=\"color:#fff; backgr