| 104&nbsp;ft\t|| 54.4&nbsp;ft\t|| 8.0&nbsp;ft\n| 2 [[GE Passport]]\t|| {{#expr:2*18920}} lbf\t|| 114,850&nbsp;lb\t|| 7,725&nbsp;nmi\t|| 475 kn\t|| {{#expr:48519/7725round2}} lb\n|}\n\n===VIP airliners ===\n\n[[File:Boeing's commercial aircraft in BBJ livery.jpg|thumb|[[Boeing Business Jet]]s are the most widespread bizliners.]]\n\n''Business airliner'' can be contracted as ''bizliner''.<ref name=\"AIN\">{{cite web |url= http://www.ainonline.com/aviation-news/business-aviation/2010-06-17/airbus-sees-great-promise-bizliner-orders-china |title= Airbus Sees Great Promise for Bizliner Orders in China |publisher= [[Aviation International News]] |author=Chad Trautvetter |date= 17 June 2010}}</ref> [[Airliner]]s converted into business jets are used by sports teams or [[VIP]]s with a large entourage or press corps. Such airplanes can face operational restrictions based on runway length or local [[noise restriction]]s. They can be the most expensive type of private jet as they provide the greatest space and capabilities.\n\nAircraft of this class include:\n* [[Airbus Corporate Jets]]<ref name=AP/><ref name=JA/><ref name=AC/><ref name=BAP/>\n* [[Boeing Business Jet]]<ref name=AP/><ref name=JA/><ref name=AC/><ref name=BAP/>\n* [[Embraer Lineage 1000]]<ref name=AP/><ref name=JA/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ VIP Airliners, 8 pax mission<ref name=PPH1805>{{cite news |url= http://aviationweek.com/site-files/aviationweek.com/files/datasheets/gated/BCA_201805.pdf |title= 2018 Business Airplanes Purchase Planning Handbook |work= Business & Commercial Aviation |publisher= Aviation Week |date= May 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n! Model !! Pax !! Length !! Span !! int. L !! int. W\n! Engines !! Thrust !! MTOW !! Range !! Cruise !! Fuel/nmi\n|-\n| [[Embraer Lineage 1000|Lineage 1000]]E\t|| 13\u201319\t|| 118.9&nbsp;ft\t|| 94.2&nbsp;ft\t|| 84.3&nbsp;ft\t|| 8.8&nbsp;ft\t|| 2 [[General Electric CF34|CF34]]\t|| {{#expr:2*18500}} lb\t|| 120,152&nbsp;lb\t|| 4,602&nbsp;nmi{{efn|name=4pax}}\t|| 446 kn\t|| {{#expr:44240/4602round2}} lb\n|-\n| [[Boeing Business Jet|BBJ MAX]]-7\t|| 19-172\t|| 116.7&nbsp;ft\t|| 117.8&nbsp;ft\t|| 85.5&nbsp;ft\t|| 11.6&nbsp;ft\n| 2 [[CFM LEAP]]\t|| {{#expr:2*29300}} lb\t|| 177,000&nbsp;lb\t|| 7,000&nbsp;nmi\t|| \t||\n|-\n| [[Boeing Business Jet|BBJ MAX]]-8\t|| 19-189\t|| 129.7&nbsp;ft\t|| 117.8&nbsp;ft\t|| 98.5&nbsp;ft\t|| 11.6&nbsp;ft\t|| 2 [[CFM LEAP]]\t|| {{#expr:2*29300}} lb\t|| 181,200&nbsp;lb\t|| 6,640&nbsp;nmi\t|| \t||\n|-\n| [[Airbus Corporate Jets|ACJ]]319\t|| 19-156\t|| 111.0&nbsp;ft\t|| 111.8&nbsp;ft\t|| 78.0&nbsp;ft\t|| 12.2&nbsp;ft\n| 2 [[CFM56]]\t|| {{#expr:2*27000}} lb\t|| 168,650&nbsp;lb\t|| 6,002&nbsp;nmi\t|| 442 kn\t|| {{#expr:65558/6002round2}} lb\n|-\n| [[Boeing Business Jet|BBJ MAX]]-9\t|| 19\u2013220\t|| 138.3&nbsp;ft\t|| 117.8&nbsp;ft\t|| 107.2&nbsp;ft\t|| 11.6&nbsp;ft\t|| 2 [[CFM LEAP]]\t|| {{#expr:2*29300}} lb\t|| 194,700&nbsp;lb\t|| 6,515&nbsp;nmi\t|| \t|| \n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{commonscat|Business jets}}\n* [[Very light jet]]\n* [[Air transports of heads of state and government]]\n* [[Supersonic business jet]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=FMvlj>{{cite magazine |url= http://www.flyingmag.com/tags/very-light-jet |title= Very light jets |magazine= [[Flying (magazine)|Flying]]}}</ref>\n<ref name=FMlj>{{cite magazine |url= http://www.flyingmag.com/tags/light-jets |title= Light jets |magazine= [[Flying (magazine)|Flying]]}}</ref>\n<ref name=FMmsj>{{cite magazine |url= http://www.flyingmag.com/tags/mid-size-jets |title= Mid-size jets |magazine= [[Flying (magazine)|Flying]]}}</ref>\n<ref name=FMsmsj>{{cite magazine |url= http://www.flyingmag.com/tags/super-mid-size-jets |title= Super mid-size jets |magazine= [[Flying (magazine)|Flying]]}}</ref>\n<ref name=FMhj>{{cite magazine |url= http://www.flyingmag.com/tags/heavy-jets |title= Heavy jets |magazine= [[Flying (magazine)|Flying]]}}</ref>\n<ref name=AP>{{cite web |url= http://www.airpartner.com/en/aircraft-guide