"\n| MI|| [[Mirzapur District|Mirzapur]]|| [[Mirzapur]]|| 2,114,852|| 4,522|| 468 || [[File:India Uttar Pradesh districts 2012 Mirzapur.svg|150px|center]]\n|- style=\"background:#f4f9ff;\"\n| MO|| [[Moradabad District|Moradabad]]|| [[Moradabad]]|| 3,749,630|| 3,648|| 1,028 || [[File:India Uttar Pradesh districts 2012 Moradabad.svg|150px|center]]\n|- style=\"background:#f4f9ff;\"\n| MU|| [[Muzaffarnagar District|Muzaffarnagar]]|| [[Muzaffarnagar]]|| 3,541,952|| 2945|| 884 || [[File:India Uttar Pradesh districts 2012 Muzaffarnagar.svg|159px|center]]\n|- style=\"background:#f4f9ff;\"\n| PI|| [[Pilibhit District|Pilibhit]]|| [[Pilibhit]]|| 1,643,788|| 3,499|| 470 || [[File:India Uttar Pradesh districts 2012 Pilibhit.svg|150px|center]]\n|- style=\"background:#f4f9ff;\"\n| PR|| [[Pratapgarh district, Uttar Pradesh|Pratapgarh]]|| [[Pratapgarh district, Uttar Pradesh|Pratapgarh]]|| 2,727,156|| 3,717|| 734 || [[File:India Uttar Pradesh districts 2012 Pratapgarh.svg|150px|center]]\n|- style=\"background:#f4f9ff;\"\n| RB|| [[Rae Bareli District|Rae Bareli]]|| [[Rae Bareli]]|| 2,872,204|| 4,609|| 623 || [[File:India Uttar Pradesh districts 2012 Raebareli.svg|150px|center]]\n|- style=\"background:#f4f9ff;\"\n| RA|| [[Rampur District|Rampur]]|| [[Rampur, Uttar Pradesh|Rampur]]|| 1,922,450|| 2,367|| 812 || [[File:India Uttar Pradesh districts 2012 Rampur.svg|150px|center]]\n|- style=\"background:#f4f9ff;\"\n| SA|| [[Saharanpur District|Saharanpur]]|| [[Saharanpur]]|| 2,848,152|| 3,860|| 772 || [[File:India Uttar Pradesh districts 2012 Saharanpur.svg|150px|center]]\n|- style=\"background:#f4f9ff;\"\n| SK|| [[Sant Kabir Nagar District|Sant Kabir Nagar]]|| [[Khalilabad, India|Khalilabad]]|| 1,714,300|| 1,659.15|| 1000 || [[File:India Uttar Pradesh districts 2012 Sant Kabir Nagar.svg|150px|center]]\n|- style=\"background:#f4f9ff;\"\n| SR|| [[Sant Ravidas Nagar]]|| [[Gyanpur]]|| 1,352,056|| 960|| 1,408 || [[File:India Uttar Pradesh districts 2012 Sant Ravidas Nagar.svg|150px|center]]\n|- style=\"background:#f4f9ff;\"\n| SM|| [[Sambhal district|Sambhal]] || [[Sambhal]] || 2,217,020|| 2452.30 || 890 || [[File:India Uttar Pradesh districts 2012 Sambhal.svg|150px|center]]\n|- style=\"background:#f4f9ff;\"\n| SJ|| [[Shahjahanpur District|Shahjahanpur]]|| [[Shahjahanpur]]|| 2,549,458|| 4,575|| 557 || [[File:India Uttar Pradesh districts 2012 Shahjahanpur.svg|150px|center]]\n|- style=\"background:#f4f9ff;\"\n| SH|| [[Shamli district|Shamli]]|| [[Shamli]]|| 1,377,840|| 1,054|| 928 || [[File:India Uttar Pradesh districts 2012 Shamli.svg|150px|center]]\n|- style=\"background:#f4f9ff;\"\n| SV|| [[Shravasti District|Shravasti]]|| [[Shravasti District|Shravasti]]|| 1,175,428|| 1,126|| 1,044 || [[File:India Uttar Pradesh districts 2012 Shravasti.svg|150px|center]]\n|- style=\"background:#f4f9ff;\"\n| SN|| [[Siddharthnagar District|Siddharthnagar]]|| [[Siddharthnagar]]|| 2,038,598|| 2,751|| 741 || [[File:India Uttar Pradesh districts 2012 Siddharthnagar.svg|150px|center]]\n|- style=\"background:#f4f9ff;\"\n| SI|| [[Sitapur District|Sitapur]]|| [[Sitapur]]|| 3,616,510|| 5,743|| 630 || [[File:India Uttar Pradesh districts 2012 Sitapur.svg|150px|center]]\n|- style=\"background:#f4f9ff;\"\n| SO|| [[Sonbhadra]]|| [[Robertsganj]]|| 1,862,612|| 6,788|| 270 || [[File:India Uttar Pradesh districts 2012 Sonbhadra.svg|150px|center]]\n|- style=\"background:#f4f9ff;\"\n| SU|| [[Sultanpur District|Sultanpur]]|| [[Sultanpur, Uttar Pradesh|Sultanpur]]|| 3,190,926|| 4,436|| 719 || [[File:India Uttar Pradesh districts 2012 Sultanpur.svg|150px|center]]\n|- style=\"background:#f4f9ff;\"\n| UN|| [[Unnao District|Unnao]]|| [[Unnao]]|| 2,700,426|| 4,558|| 592 || [[File:India Uttar Pradesh districts 2012 Unnao.svg|150px|center]]\n|- style=\"background:#f4f9ff;\"\n| VA|| [[Varanasi District|Varanasi (Kashi)]]|| [[Varanasi ]]|| 3,147,927|| 1,578|| 1,995 || [[File:India Uttar Pradesh districts 2012 Varanasi.svg|150px|center]]\n|- style=\"background:#f4f9ff;\"\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Divisions of Uttar Pradesh]]\n* [[List of RTO districts in India#UP\u2014Uttar Pradesh|List of  districts in Uttar Pradesh]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Districts of Uttar Pradesh}}\n{{Districts of India}}\n{{Uttar Pradesh topics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Districts Of Uttar Pradesh}}\n[[Category:Districts of Uttar Pradesh| ]]\n[[Category:Uttar Pradesh-related lists]]\n[[Category:Lists of districts in India|Uttar Pradesh]]\n", "name_user": "103.51.233.232", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Faizabad has been replaced with Ayodhya)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_districts_of_Uttar_Pradesh"}
{"title_page": "El Salvador national football team", "text_new": "{{short description|Men's national association football team}}\n{{About|the men's team|the women's team|El Salvador women's national football team}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox national football team\n| Name               = El Salvador\n| Badge              = \n| Badge_size         = 200px\n| Nickname           = ''La Seleccion'' <br> ''Los cuzcatlecos'' <br> ''La azul y Blanco''\n| Association        = [[Salvadoran Football Federation]]\n| Sub-confederation  = {{nowrap|[[Central American Football Union|UNCAF]] (Central America)}}\n| Confederation      = [[CONCACAF]]\n| Coach              = [[Carlos de los Cobos]]<ref>https://www.fifa.com/associations/association=SLV/about.html</ref>\n| Captain            = [[Henry Hernandez]]\n| Most caps          = {{unbulleted list|[[Alfredo Pacheco]] (86)}} \n| Top scorer         = [[Raul Diaz Arce]] (39)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/elsal-recintlp.html#goals|title=El Salvador - Record International Players|author=|date=|work=rsssf.com|accessdate=4 January 2017}}</ref>\n| Home Stadium       = [[Estadio Cuscatl\u00e1n]]\n| FIFA Trigramme     = SLV\n| FIFA Rank          = {{FIFA World Rankings|SLV}}\n| FIFA max           = 49\n| FIFA max date      = April 2012\n| FIFA min           = 190\n| FIFA min date      = November 2006\n| Elo Rank           = {{World Football Elo Ratings|El Salvador}}\n| Elo max            = 40\n| Elo max date       = December 1943\n| Elo min            = 125\n| Elo min date       = April 2007\n| pattern_la1        = _slv19h\n| pattern_b1         = _slv19h\n| pattern_ra1        = _slv19h\n| pattern_sh1        = _slv19h\n| pattern_so1        = _slv19h\n| leftarm1           = 0022FF\n| body1              = 0022FF\n| rightarm1          = 0022FF\n| shorts1            = 0022FF\n| socks1             = 0022FF\n| pattern_la2        = _slv19a\n| pattern_b2         = _slv19a\n| pattern_ra2        = _slv19a\n| pattern_sh2        = _slv19a\n| pattern_so2        = _slv19a\n| leftarm2           = FFFFFF\n| body2              = FFFFFF\n| rightarm2          = FFFFFF\n| shorts2            = FFFFFF\n| socks2             = FFFFFF\n| First game         = {{fb|CRC}} 7\u20130 {{fb-rt|SLV}} <br /> ([[Guatemala City]], [[Guatemala]]; 14 September 1921)\n| Largest win        = {{fb|SLV}} 12\u20130 {{fb-rt|AIA}} <br> ([[San Salvador]], [[El Salvador]]; 6 February 2008)\n| Largest loss       = {{fb|HUN}} 10\u20131 {{fb-rt|SLV}} <br> ([[Elche]], [[Spain]]; 15 June 1982)\n| World cup apps     = 2\n| World cup first    = 1970\n| World cup best     = Group stage ([[1970 FIFA World Cup|1970]], [[1982 FIFA World Cup|1982]])\n| Regional name      = [[CONCACAF Championship]] & [[CONCACAF Gold Cup|Gold Cup]]\n| Regional cup apps  = 17\n| Regional cup first = [[1963 CONCACAF Championship|1963]]\n| Regional cup best  = Runners-up ([[1963 CONCACAF Championship|1963]], [[1981 CONCACAF Championship|1981]])\n| medaltemplates     = \n{{MedalCompetition | [[CONCACAF Championship]]}}\n{{MedalSilver | '''[[1963 CONCACAF Championship|1963 El Salvador]]''' | NA}}\n{{MedalBronze | '''[[1977 CONCACAF Championship|1977 Mexico]]''' | NA}}\n{{MedalSilver | '''[[1981 CONCACAF Championship|1981 Honduras]]''' | NA}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[UNCAF Nations Cup]]}}\n{{MedalBronze | '''[[1995 UNCAF Nations Cup|1995 El Salvador]]''' | NA}}\n{{MedalBronze | '''[[1997 UNCAF Nations Cup|1997 Guatemala]]''' | NA}}\n{{MedalBronze | '''[[2001 UNCAF Nations Cup|2001 Honduras]]''' | NA}}\n{{MedalBronze | '''[[2003 UNCAF Nations Cup|2003 Panama]]''' | NA}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Central American and Caribbean Games]]}}\n{{MedalBronze | '''[[1935 Central American and Caribbean Games|1935 San Salvador]]''' | NA}}\n{{MedalGold | '''[[1954 Central American and Caribbean Games|1954 Mexico City]]''' | NA}}\n{{MedalGold | '''[[2002 Central American and Caribbean Games|2002 San Salvador]]''' | NA}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[CCCF Championship]]}}\n{{MedalSilver | '''[[1941 CCCF Championship|1941 San Jos\u00e9]]''' | NA}}\n{{MedalGold | '''[[1943 CCCF Championship|1943 San Salvador]]''' | NA}}\n{{MedalSilver | '''[[1961 CCCF Championship|1961 San Jos\u00e9]]''' | NA}}\n}}\n\nThe '''El Salvador national football team''' ({{lang-es|Selecci\u00f3n de F\u00fatbol de El Salvador}}) represents [[El Salvador]] in international [[association football|football]], and is governed by the [[Salvadoran Football Federation]] (FESFUT).<ref>https://www.elgrafico.com/futbol/La-actividad-de-la-seleccion-en-2018-20180123-0008.html</ref>\n\nIn 1899, two teams from [[Santa Ana, El Salvador|Santa Ana]] and [[San Salvador, El Salvador|San Salvador]] met for the first known football game in El Salvador. The national team's first match was played in September 1921, when they were invited to participate in [[Independence Centenary Games|a tournament]] to celebrate 100 years of [[Central American declarations of independence|Central American Independence]].\n\nEl Salvador has made two [[FIFA World Cup]] appearances: first in [[1970 FIFA World Cup|1970]] and again in [[1982 FIFA World Cup|1982]], but have never progressed beyond the first stage of a finals tournament. They were the [[1943 CCCF Championship|1943 CCCF]] champions, and finished in second-place in the [[1941 CCCF Championship|1941]] and [[1961 CCCF Championship|1961]] championships. They have competed in the [[CONCACAF Championship|CONCACAF regional tournaments]] fourteen times, finishing as runners-up in [[1963 CONCACAF Championship|1963]] and [[1981 CONCACAF Championship|1981]]. ''La Selecta'' also competes in the biennial [[Central American Cup|UNCAF Nations Cup]], the [[Football at the Pan American Games|Pan American Games]], the [[Football at the Summer Olympics|Olympics]], and have won two gold medals in the [[Central American and Caribbean Games]].<ref>http://www.elgrafico.com/2017/12/07/el-salvador-celebra-15-aos-del-oro-en-los-centroamericanos-y-del-caribe</ref>\n\nThe [[Estadio Cuscatl\u00e1n]], also known as \"El Coloso de Montserrat\" and \"La Catedral del Espect\u00e1culo\", is the official home stadium of the El Salvador national football team. Since 2008, the national team has had a [[Kit (association football)|kit]] sponsorship contract with England-based supplier [[Mitre Sports International|Mitre]]. [[Ra\u00fal D\u00edaz Arce]] is the all-time top-scorer for the national team, with 39 goals, while [[Alfredo Pacheco]] has the most caps, with 85 appearances.\n\n==History==\n===Beginnings===\n[[Salvadoran Football Association|Salvadoran football]] had its origins in the city of [[Santa Ana, El Salvador|Santa Ana]], on a field called \"Campo Marte\". This was the first time a [[Association football|football]] game was hosted in El Salvador. That first game took place on July 26, 1899 among players from [[Santa Ana, El Salvador|Santa Ana]] and [[San Salvador]]. Both teams had several foreign players from [[England]] who are credited with introducing football to El Salvador. The home team won the game 2\u20130.<ref name=\"History\">{{cite web |url=http://www.elbaloncuscatleco.com/historia.html |title=Historia |author=Gomez, Omar |work= |publisher=El Balon Cusctatleco |accessdate=16 May 2011 |language=Spanish |trans-title=History}}</ref>\n\nAlthough El Salvador played a few games in the early part of the 20th century, they did not form an official national team until 1921 when players such as Jos\u00e9 Pablo Huezo, Carlos Escobar Leiva or Santiago Barrachina revolutionized football in the country.<ref name=\"Name\">{{cite web|last=Hatcher|first=Dan|title=El Salvador Soccer Team Name Ideas|url=http://danhatcher.com/blog/tag/soccer-team-name-ideas/|accessdate=2010-11-01|date=2008-09-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708224217/http://danhatcher.com/blog/tag/soccer-team-name-ideas/|archive-date=2011-07-08|url-status=dead}}</ref>  In September 1921, El Salvador were invited to [[Guatemala]] to take part in the [[Independence Centenary Games]], to celebrate 100 years of [[Central American declarations of independence|Central American Independence]].<ref name=\"Start\">{{cite web |url=http://www.elsalvador.com/especiales/2008/selecta2008/historia.asp |title=Nace la pasion... |work= |publisher=elsalvador.com |accessdate=16 May 2011 |language=Spanish |trans-title=The passion is born... }}</ref><ref name=\"History of the team\">{{cite web |url=http://fesfut.org.sv/historia.php |title=Historia del F\u00fatbol Salvadore\u00f1o |work= |publisher=fesfut.org.sv |accessdate=16 May 2011 |language=Spanish |trans-title=History of Salvadoran Football}}</ref> The tournament was between [[Guatemala national football team|Guatemala]], [[Honduras national football team|Honduras]], [[Costa Rica national football team|Costa Rica]], and El Salvador. The Guatemalans and Costa Ricans had more experience with football than the Salvadorans and Hondurans.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elsalvador.com/noticias/EDH_DEPORTES/figurauydeportes/Portada.pdf|title=el nacimiento de 'la selecta'|publisher=El Diario de Hoy|accessdate=28 August 2011|language=Spanish|format=PDF|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121004140122/http://www.elsalvador.com/noticias/EDH_DEPORTES/figurauydeportes/Portada.pdf|archive-date=4 October 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> It was a [[single-elimination tournament]] with Guatemala playing Honduras and El Salvador playing Costa Rica. El Salvador, which were dressed with white shorts and black shirt, utilized the classic [[2\u20133\u20135]] scheme with Carlos Escobar Leyva; Spanish resident Santiago Barrachina, Jos\u00e9 Pablo Huezo; Benjam\u00edn Sandoval, Emilio Dawson, and Frenchman Emilio Detruit; V\u00edctor Recinos, brothers Guillermo and Jos\u00e9 E. Alcaine, Guillermo Sandoval and Enrique Lindo. By halftime Costa Rica was up 3\u20130, and at the final whistle after 80 minutes (40 minutes for each half) won 7\u20130.<ref name=\"Matches\">{{cite web | url= http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/elsal-intres.html |title= 1921 to 2008 El Salvador match results by \"Barrie Courtney\" |publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]]| accessdate=16 May 2011 | date=}}</ref> Despite the loss, this tournament was the starting point of the official El Salvador national team.\n\nOther than the tournament, El Salvador only played international friendlies (all against Costa Rica and Honduras) for the rest of the 1920s. El Salvador lost their first friendly 3\u20130 against Costa Rica, while the second and third ended in a 1\u20130 loss and 0\u20130 draw against Honduras.<ref name=\"Matches\"/> On 7 December 1928, El Salvador recorded its first ever win: a 5\u20130 victory over Honduras, the team that would become their traditional rivals. The game was played at Campo Marte, [[San Salvador, El Salvador|San Salvador]], and was not only El Salvador's first ever recorded win, but also the first time the team had scored in an international match. Gustavo \"Taviche\" Marroqu\u00edn scored every goal, becoming the first ever Salvadoran player to score five goals in a single game for the El Salvador national football team<ref name=\"Matches\"/> (a feat later equaled by [[Miguel Cruz]] and [[Rudis Corrales]]).\n\n===1930s===\nIn the early 1930s, El Salvador appointed its first official national coach, American [[Mark Scott Thompson]], in preparation for the [[Football at the 1930 Central American and Caribbean Games|1930 Central American and Caribbean Games]] in [[Havana, Cuba]].<ref name=\"Directores\">{{cite web |url=http://www.elbaloncuscatleco.com/directores.html |title=Los Directores en La Selecta |author=Gomez, Omar |work= |publisher=El Balon Cuscatleco |accessdate=16 May 2011 |language=Spanish |trans-title=The Directors of ''La Selecta''}}</ref> El Salvador finished in fourth place at the games.<ref name=\"jdcac\">{{cite web |url=http://www.elbaloncuscatleco.com/jdcac.html |title=El Salvador en Los Juegos Deportivos |author=Gomez, Omar |work= |publisher=El Balon Cuscatleco |accessdate=16 May 2011 |language=Spanish |trans-title=El Salvador in Sportive Games}}</ref> The [[Federaci\u00f3n Salvadore\u00f1a de F\u00fatbol]], the official governing [[Association football|football]] organization in El Salvador, was founded in 1935. By this time, El Salvador were coached by Spaniard [[Pablo Ferre El\u00edas]].<ref name=\"Directores\"/> The El Salvador-hosted [[Football at the 1935 Central American and Caribbean Games|1935 Central American and Caribbean Games]] took place in the new government funded [[Estadio Jorge \"M\u00e1gico\" Gonz\u00e1lez|Estadio Flor Blanca]], at that time the biggest stadium in the country. The Salvadoran squad consisted of Edmundo Majano as goalkeeper; Tobias Rivera and Ra\u00fal Castro in defense; Am\u00e9rico Gonzalez and Napoleon Ca\u00f1as as midfielders; and \u00c1lex Morales, Rogelio Aviles, Fidel Quintanilla, Miguel \"Americano\" Cruz, and Andr\u00e9s Hern\u00e1ndez as strikers. Previously the national team had worn black and white striped jerseys and this was the first time they turned out in a blue strip. The team improved their performance over the previous competition to finish in third place as bronze medal winners.<ref name=\"jdcac\"/><ref name=\"CAG 1935\">{{cite web |author=Garin, Erik |author2=Morrison, Neil |title= Central American Games 1935 (El Salvador) | url= http://www.rsssf.com/tablesc/cag35.html| publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]] | accessdate=14 May 2011 | date=21 Apr 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 1938, the [[Federaci\u00f3n Salvadore\u00f1a de F\u00fatbol]] became affiliates of [[FIFA]].<ref name=\"FIFA\">{{cite web | title= El Salvador| url= https://www.fifa.com/associations/association=slv/index.html | publisher=[[FIFA]] | accessdate=16 May 2011 | date=}}</ref> Once again the El Salvador national football team participated in the [[Football at the 1938 Central American and Caribbean Games|1938 Central American and Caribbean Games]], hosted in [[Panama]], which were won by [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]] with Costa Rica in second place. El Salvador won two games and lost three out of the five played. A match for third place between Colombia and El Salvador was scheduled but was cancelled due to the bad physical state of the players. El Salvador finished in fourth place by goal difference.<ref name=\"jdcac\"/><ref name=\"CAC 1938\">{{cite web |author1=Frank Ballesteros |author2=Myk Cameron |author3=Barrie Courtney |author4=Erik Garin |author5=Neil Morrison |title= Central American and Caribbean Games Games 1938 (Panama) | url= http://www.rsssf.com/tablesc/cag38.html| publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]] | accessdate=14 May 2011 | date=24 Feb 2004}}</ref>\n\n===1940s===\nOn April 26, 1940, the first national football federation was approved, with Dr. Luis Rivas Palacios as president. In 1941, the first international competition in [[CONCACAF]], the international governing body for football in North America, Central America and the Caribbean, the [[CCCF Championship|Central American and Caribbean Championship (CCCF)]] took place in Costa Rica. El Salvador took part for the first time alongside Costa Rica, [[Cura\u00e7ao national football team|Cura\u00e7ao]], [[Nicaragua national football team|Nicaragua]], and Panama. El Salvador were runners-up, recording two wins, one tie, and one loss.<ref name=\"CCCF 1941\"/>\n\nThe [[1943 CCCF Championship]] took place in San Salvador with the participation of Costa Rica, Guatemala, and Nicaragua. El Salvador was coached by former national player [[Am\u00e9rico Gonz\u00e1lez (footballer)|Am\u00e9rico Gonz\u00e1lez]]. At the end of the tournament, El Salvador and Guatemala ended up with the same number of points and so had to play a tiebreaker. On December 21, Guatemala failed to show up for the match resulting in El Salvador declaring themselves 1943 CCCF Championship winners by goal difference. This was the country's first international title. El Salvador's 10\u20121 set the team's record for the most goals scored in a single game yet . It was also the second time a Salvadoran player (Miguel \"Americano\" Cruz) had scored five goals in a single match.<ref name=\"CCCF 1943\"/> El Salvador defended their title in the [[1946 CCCF Championship]], hosted in [[Costa Rica]], alongside six other participants. ''La Selecta'' finished in third place, winning three matches and losing two. In the [[1948 CCCF Championship]], hosted in [[Guatemala]], Costa Rica won the championship for the third time, with El Salvador finishing in fifth place.\n\n===1950s===\nEl Salvador did not participate in qualification for the subsequent World Cups in [[1954 FIFA World Cup|1954]], [[1958 FIFA World Cup|1958]], [[1962 FIFA World Cup|1962]], and [[1966 FIFA World Cup|1966]]. Reasons for these refusals are unknown but might be due to the cost of travel, since at that time the team had never played so far from home.{{citation needed|date=September 2015}} During these years El Salvador had a good squad, with players like goalkeeper Manuel \"Tamal\u00f3n\" Garay, Rafael \"Chapuda\" Reyes, Conrado Miranda, Miguel \"Americano\" Cruz, Rafael Corado and Mando Rivas.\n\nIn the group stage of the [[Football at the 1950 Central American and Caribbean Games|1950 Central American and Caribbean Games]] in Mexico, El Salvador recorded two wins, one tie, and one loss. They began the final round by beating Cura\u00e7ao 3\u20131, but lost their other two matches leaving them in fifth place.<ref name=\"jdcac\"/> In 1953, the El Salvador national football team took part in its fifth CCCF Championship, the [[1953 CCCF Championship]], hosted in [[Costa Rica]], together with seven other national teams. [[Costa Rica]] became champions for the fourth time, and El Salvador finished in fifth place again.\n\nAt the [[Football at the 1954 Central American and Caribbean Games|1954 Central American and Caribbean Games]] El Salvador won their second international title under the direction of coach [[Carbilio Tomasino]], with a team consisting of Yohalmo Aurora, Manuel \"Tamal\u00f3n\" Garay, Hugo Moreno, Armando Lar\u00edn, Luis Regalado, Conrado Miranda, Fernando Barrios, Ram\u00f3n \"Pezote\" Ch\u00e1vez, Jos\u00e9 Hern\u00e1ndez, Mario Montoya, Juan Francisco \"Cariota\" Barraza, Ricardo \"Chilenito\" Valencia, Alfredo \"Baiza\" Ruano, and Obdulio Hern\u00e1ndez. They debuted against [[Colombia national football team|Colombia]] in a 2\u20132 tie, beat [[Cuba national football team|Cuba]] 3\u20131, beat Mexico 3\u20132 and finally beat Panama 1\u20130 with a goal by \"Cariota\" Barraza. The 3\u20132 victory against Mexico, with two goals from Mario Montoya (16',36')<ref name=\"Minute goal scored\" group=\"note\"/> and one from Ricardo Valencia (37'), was the first victory by a Central American team against Mexico.<ref name=\"jdcac\"/>\n\nIn the [[1955 CCCF Championship]], hosted in Honduras, Costa Rica crowned themselves champions for the fifth time with El Salvador finishing in 4th place. This marked the sixth time El Salvador participated in the CCCF Championship. For unknown reasons they didn't participate in the [[1957 CCCF Championship|1957]] and [[1960 CCCF Championship|1960]] CCCF Championships.\n\n===1960s===\nEl Salvador returned to participate in the [[1961 CCCF Championship]], hosted in Costa Rica, alongside nine other national teams. Due to the larger number of teams the CCCF Championship shifted to a two-round format with two [[Round-robin tournament|round-robin]] group stages. In the first round, there were two groups, one with five teams and one with four. The top two teams from both groups advanced to the second stage. El Salvador was placed in the four team group [[Honduras]], the [[Netherlands Antilles]], and [[Nicaragua]], which they topped with two wins and one draw. In the decisive round they finished in second place behind Costa Rica, who won their seventh CCCF Championship. Afterward the tournament was dissolved and replaced with the [[CONCACAF Championship]].\n\n[[1963 CONCACAF Championship|The first CONCACAF Championship was hosted in 1963]] and El Salvador hosted both the qualification round and final tournament. There were nine other participants, with the format the same as the final CCCF Championship. Costa Rica became the first CONCACAF champions, and El Salvador finished as runners-up.<ref name=\"CONCACAF Nations Cup 1963\"/> In 1964 Chilean [[Hern\u00e1n Carrasco Vivanco]], who would later revolutionize Salvadoran football, became coach of the national team. He led the national team for the first time at the [[1965 CONCACAF Championship]], hosted in Guatemala, where they won 2 games, tied 1 game, and lost two, finishing in fourth place. In 1966 the El Salvador football team took part in the Central American and Caribbean Games for the sixth time in a [[1966 Central American and Caribbean Games|competition]] that took place in [[Puerto Rico]]. The national team participated alongside seven other teams, finishing in fourth place.<ref name=\"jdcac\"/> In 1968 El Salvador qualified for the [[1968 Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]] for the first time.<ref name=\"olimpicos\">{{cite web | author=Gomez, Omar | title=El Salvador en Juegos Olimpicos |language=Spanish | url= http://www.elbaloncuscatleco.com/olimpicos.html | publisher=Elbaloncuscatleco.com | accessdate=2011-08-21 | date=}}</ref> They lost 4\u20130 to [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]],<ref name=\"Hungary 1968\">{{cite web|publisher=FIFA|title=Olympic Football Tournament Mexico City 1968 Hungary-El Salvador|url=https://www.fifa.com/tournaments/archive/tournament=512/edition=197099/matches/match=32096/report.html|accessdate=2011-02-08|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090902222115/http://www.fifa.com/tournaments/archive/tournament%3D512/edition%3D197099/matches/match%3D32096/report.html|archivedate=2009-09-02}}</ref> 3\u20131 to [[Israel national football team|Israel]],<ref name=\"Israel 1968\">{{cite web|publisher=FIFA|title=Olympic Football Tournament Mexico City 1968 Israel-El Salvador|url=https://www.fifa.com/tournaments/archive/tournament=512/edition=197099/matches/match=32103/report.html|accessdate=2011-02-08|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120902062125/http://www.fifa.com/tournaments/archive/tournament%3D512/edition%3D197099/matches/match%3D32103/report.html|archivedate=2012-09-02}}</ref> and tied 1\u20131 with [[Ghana national football team|Ghana]].<ref name=\"Ghana 1968\">{{cite web|publisher=FIFA|title=Olympic Football Tournament Mexico City 1968 Ghana-El Salvador|url=https://www.fifa.com/tournaments/archive/tournament=512/edition=197099/matches/match=32111/report.html|accessdate=2011-02-08|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120929072158/http://www.fifa.com/tournaments/archive/tournament%3D512/edition%3D197099/matches/match%3D32111/report.html|archivedate=2012-09-29}}</ref> The coach by this time was [[Rigoberto Guzm\u00e1n]].\n\nGregorio Bundio and his assistant Jos\u00e9 Santacolomba coached the team in the [[1970 FIFA World Cup qualification|qualifying stages]] for the [[1970 FIFA World Cup]]. This was the first time El Salvador participated in World Cup qualifying. As host, Mexico automatically qualified so there was just one qualification spot up for grabs. El Salvador won group 3, playing four games, winning three and losing one. Their record was 10 goals for and 5 goals against with 6 points. As a result, they qualified for a 3-game playoff against group 2 winner and traditional rival, Honduras. The first game, hosted on 8 June 1969 in the Honduran capital of [[Tegucigalpa]], was won 1\u20130 by the home team and was followed by crowd violence. The second game, hosted on 15 June 1969 in the Salvadoran capital of [[San Salvador]], was won 3\u20130 by El Salvador, and was followed by even greater violence.<ref>{{cite book |title=Wars and Peace Treaties, 1816\u20131991 |last=Goldstein |first=Erik |year=1992 |publisher=Routledge |location= |isbn=978-0-203-97682-1 |pages=195\u20136 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VjWnMm53xQ8C&pg=PA195&dq=football+war+honduras+el+salvador# |accessdate=4 July 2010 }}</ref> A play-off match took place in [[Mexico City]] on 26 June 1969. El Salvador won 3\u20132 after [[extra time]]. As a result of existing tensions being exacerbated by these matches, on 14 July 1969 the two countries began the 100-hour-long war known as the [[Football War]]. As a result of the conflict, El Salvador and Honduras were both disqualified from entering the [[1969 CONCACAF Championship qualification]].\n\nThe final set of qualifying games for the [[1970 FIFA World Cup|1970 World Cup]] took place against [[Haiti]]. The first leg was won by El Salvador in Haiti, 2\u20131, with goals from Elver Acevedo (43') and Mauricio 'Pipo' Rodr\u00edguez (62'). The second leg was lost 3\u20130. The playoff game on 8 October 1969 was won by El Salvador with a goal by Juan Ram\u00f3n \"Mon\" Mart\u00ednez (14' a.e.t.). Thus the El Salvador national football team qualified for their first World Cup, even though it was their first time attempting qualification.\n\n\"El Pajaro Pic\u00f3n Pic\u00f3n\" was a Colombian song written by Eliseo Herrera which was very popular in El Salvador during the qualifying stages of the 1970 World Cup. During a radio show, Mauricio Boj\u00f3rquez parodied the song, which he named \"Arriba con la Selecci\u00f3n\". That parody became so famous that it became the official anthem of the El Salvador national football team.<ref name=\"Official anthem\">{{cite web |url=http://lacomunidad.elpais.com/deralte/2011/1/17/el-pajaro-picon-picon-y-guerra-del-futbol |title=El P\u00e1jaro Pic\u00f3n y La Guerra de F\u00fatbol |language=Spanish |publisher=lacomunidad.elpais.com |accessdate=17 January 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110509031600/http://lacomunidad.elpais.com/deralte/2011/1/17/el-pajaro-picon-picon-y-guerra-del-futbol |archive-date=9 May 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===1970s===\nIn the World Cup finals El Salvador was drawn into a group with [[Belgium national football team|Belgium]], [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]], and the [[Soviet Union national football team|Soviet Union]]. El Salvador lost their first game 3\u20130 to Belgium in Mexico City on June 3.<ref name=\"Belgium1\">{{cite web |title=FIFA Match Report for Belgium-El Salvador on June 3, 1970 |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/edition=32/results/matches/match=1747/report.html |publisher=[[FIFA]] |accessdate=2010-11-14 | date=2006-04-12}}</ref> The second match was played against the host nation, Mexico, on 7 June. The game was decided by a controversial call near the end of the first half, with the score still at 0\u20130. Egyptian referee Hussain Kandil awarded a free kick to El Salvador in their own half. However, a Mexican player took the free-kick, passing to another Mexican player who scored. The Salvadoran players protested vigorously, to the extent of physically jostling Bermudan linesman Keith Dunstan, but the goal was allowed to stand. El Salvador restarted the game by kicking the ball into the crowd in protest. They eventually lost the game 4\u20130.<ref name=\"Mexico\">{{cite web| title= FIFA Match Report for Mexico-El Salvador on June 7, 1970| url= https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/edition=32/results/matches/match=1820/report.html| publisher= [[FIFA]]| accessdate= 2010-11-11| date= 2007-09-20| url-status= dead| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100615211242/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/edition%3D32/results/matches/match%3D1820/report.html| archivedate= June 15, 2010}}</ref> The team's third and final game occurred on June 10 with El Salvador losing 2\u20130 to the Soviet Union in Mexico City, to finish at the bottom of Group A with 0 points.<ref name=\"USSR1\">{{cite web | title=FIFA Match Report for Soviet Union-El Salvador on June 10, 1970 | url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/edition=32/results/matches/match=1823/report.html | publisher=[[FIFA]] | accessdate=2010-11-11 | date=2006-04-12 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071016132727/http://fifa.com/worldcup/archive/edition%3D32/results/matches/match%3D1823/report.html | archivedate=October 16, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nEl Salvador advanced from the first round of [[1971 CONCACAF Championship qualification]] with an aggregate score of 4\u20132 against [[Nicaragua national football team|Nicaragua]] after home and away legs. In the second round, El Salvador withdrew from the playoff when they had to play against Honduras, meaning Honduras qualified by default. The national team also took part in the [[1973 CONCACAF Championship qualification]], which doubled as qualification for the [[1974 FIFA World Cup]], but they did not advance to the [[1973 CONCACAF Championship|final stage]] after they were eliminated by [[Guatemala national football team|Guatemala]] with an aggregate score of 0\u20132 (0\u20131, 0\u20131).<ref name=\"Aggregate score\" group=\"note\"/><ref name=\"cm\">{{cite web | title=El Salvador en eliminatorias rumbo a La Copa Mundo  |language=Spanish | url= http://www.elbaloncuscatleco.com/cm.html | publisher=Elbaloncuscatleco.com | accessdate=2011-04-21 | date=}}</ref> The team was managed by [[Hector D'Angelo]].<ref name=\"Directores\"/>\n\nEl Salvador participated at the [[Pan American Games]] for the first time in 1975 at the [[Football at the 1975 Pan American Games|VII (7) Pan American Games]], hosted in [[Mexico]]. The national team participated in a group that included [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]], [[Costa Rica national football team|Costa Rica]], and Nicaragua. They debuted with a 4\u20131 win against Nicaragua on October 14 with 3 goals from [[Norberto Huezo|\"Pajarito\" Huezo]] and the debut of [[Jos\u00e9 Francisco Jovel|Francisco \"Paco\" Jovel]]. Then they played against Brazil on the 15th and lost 0\u20132. They ended the tournament by playing against Costa Rica, where they tied 0\u20130, and wherein [[Luis Ram\u00edrez Zapata|\"Pel\u00e9\" Zapata]] missed a penalty. They finished at third place in Group D, failing to advance to the next round.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[RSSSF]]|author=Garin, Erik|title=Panamerican Games 1975 (Mexico)|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesp/panam75.html|date=2008-11-27}}</ref>\n\nIn [[1977 CONCACAF Championship qualification]] ''La Selecta'' played against three other teams (Costa Rica, Guatemala, and Panama) in a home-and-away round-robin group. The top two finishers advanced [[1977 CONCACAF Championship|final tournament]]. Guatemala won the group and El Salvador was runner\u2013up. In the finals, hosted in Mexico, El Salvador played five games; they won two, drew one, and lost two. They finished in third place, below Haiti and Mexico (with the hosts winning the tournament).<ref name=\"cm\"/>  El Salvador participated in the [[1978 Central American and Caribbean Games]], hosted in [[Colombia]], marking the seventh time El Salvador participated in this competition. For the fourth time, Cuba was crowned champions. El Salvador finished in ninth place.<ref name=\"jdcac\"/>\n\n===1980s===\nEl Salvador played Costa Rica, Guatemala, Honduras and Panama in [[1981 CONCACAF Championship qualification]], once again in a home-and-away round-robin group with the top two teams advancing to the [[1981 CONCACAF Championship|final tournament]]. El Salvador and Honduras finished with equal points at the top of the group, with Honduras winning the group on goal difference. Once again the finals doubled up as World Cup qualification, this time for the [[1982 FIFA World Cup|1982 World Cup]], with the top two of the six teams qualifying. Going into the final matches, El Salvador had four points and were in third place on goal difference, with [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]] and [[Canada men's national soccer team|Canada]] both also having four points, behind Honduras with seven. On 19 November 1981, El Salvador beat [[Haiti national football team|Haiti]] 1\u20130, with a penalty by [[Norberto Huezo]]. On 21 November, Canada drew 2\u20132 with [[Cuba national football team|Cuba]] and were eliminated. In the decisive match the following day, Honduras and Mexico drew 0\u20130, meaning El Salvador qualified for the World Cup for the second time.\n\nEl Salvador took a 20-man squad to Spain, two players short of the maximum number allowed, as a controversial cost\u2013saving measure. They were coached by [[Mauricio Alonso Rodr\u00edguez|Mauricio \"Pipo\" Rodr\u00edguez]].<ref name=\"cm82\">{{cite web | title=La historia de la clasificacion a la Copa Mundo 1982  |language=Spanish | url= http://www.elbaloncuscatleco.com/cm82.html | publisher=Elbaloncuscatleco.com | accessdate=2011-04-21 | date=}}</ref><ref name=\"CONCACAF Nations Cup 1981\"/>. In their first match on 15 June in [[Elche]], they were defeated 10\u20131 by [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]], a World Cup Finals record margin of victory.<ref name=\"Hungary1\">{{cite web | title=Did You Know? table | url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/edition=32/results/matches/match=1823/report.html | publisher=[[FIFA]] | accessdate=2006-04-12 | date=2010-11-11 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071016132727/http://fifa.com/worldcup/archive/edition%3D32/results/matches/match%3D1823/report.html | archivedate=2007-10-16 }}</ref> A silver lining was that [[Luis Ram\u00edrez Zapata|Luis Baltazar Ram\u00edrez Zapata]] scored the country's first World Cup goal during the game, albeit when the Salvadorans were already 5\u20130 down.<ref name=\"Hungary2\">{{cite web | title=FIFA Match Report for Hungary-El Salvador on June 15, 1982 | url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/edition=59/results/matches/match=896/report.html | publisher=[[FIFA]] | accessdate=2010-11-11 | date=2006-04-12 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100615211424/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/edition%3D59/results/matches/match%3D896/report.html | archivedate=June 15, 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2014/may/20/25-world-cup-stunning-moments-el-salvador-hungary-spain-1982|title= World Cup: 25 stunning moments ... No18: El Salvador humiliated in Spain|date=20 May 2014|work=Guardian|accessdate=2 April 2015}}</ref> When Zapata scored, some Salvadorans cried out not to celebrate the goal because it might make the Hungarians angry and encourage them to score more.{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}. Displaying much-improved levels of organisation and commitment, El Salvador lost 1\u20130 to [[Belgium national football team|Belgium]] on 19 June in Elche and 2\u20130 to the world champions, [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]], on 23 June in [[Alicante]].<ref name=\"Belgium2\">{{cite web| title= FIFA Match Report for Belgium-El Salvador on June 19, 1982| url= https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/edition=59/results/matches/match=774/report.html| publisher= [[FIFA]]| accessdate= 2010-11-12| date= 2006-04-12| url-status= dead| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100615211429/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/edition%3D59/results/matches/match%3D774/report.html| archivedate= June 15, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"Argentina2\">{{cite web | title= FIFA Match Report for Argentina-El Salvador on June 23, 1982 | url= https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/edition=59/results/matches/match=751/report.html | publisher= [[FIFA]] | accessdate= 2010-11-11 | date= 2006-04-12 | url-status= dead | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100615211433/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/edition%3D59/results/matches/match%3D751/report.html | archivedate= June 15, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nThere were several reasons the tournament went so badly for El Salvador. First of all, their reduced squad meant that they omitted Gilberto Quinteros and Miguel Gonz\u00e1lez. According to [[Luis Guevara Mora]], the 20-year-old goalkeeper, the [[Salvadoran Football Federation]] decided to take members of the Federation, as well as their friends and family, and spent so much money they could not afford to bring a full squad.{{citation needed|date=September 2015}} The team took many stops throughout Europe under the direction of the Federation, taking three days to arrive in Spain and were the last team to do so. Once they arrived, there was more trouble. [[Adidas]] sent four white and three blue uniforms for each player, but only three white and one blue arrived. The remaining uniforms were said to have been taken away by the association.{{citation needed|date=September 2015}} They decided to play with the white uniform and keep the blue as a keepsake. Next, someone stole the balls that the team needed to train with. The day before the match against Hungary, the Hungarians had the 25 balls the organization had given them while El Salvador had none and were unable to train.{{citation needed|date=September 2015}} To make things even worse, El Salvador had never seen Hungary play, and the only knowledge that they had about the team was an outdated video that they had bought.{{cn|date=April 2020}} On the field there were more problems. Hungary's fourth goal was caused by [[Jos\u00e9 Francisco Jovel|Francisco Jovel]]'s sudden deafness after he had received a heavy blow on the cheek. When Guevara Mora called to him to stop a ball, the defender did not hear him, and the ball went past Jovel in front of the net.{{cn|date=April 2020}} After the match, the Salvadoran squad had a tense meeting with the coaching staff and Federation. The coach was dismissed immediately and the matches against Belgium and Argentina were managed by players Jovel, Huezo and Fagoaga.<ref name=\"cm82-mundial\">{{cite web|last=Gomez|first=Omar|title=El Salvador en la Copa Mundo 1982|url=http://www.elbaloncuscatleco.com/cm82-mundial.html|publisher=elbaloncuscatleco.com|accessdate=2011-08-24|language=Spanish}}</ref> Although the tournament overall was a big disappointment, Jorge \"M\u00e1gico\" Gonz\u00e1lez was considered by the national and international press as the best player,{{cn|date=April 2020}} and he stayed in Spain to play for [[C\u00e1diz CF]] and [[Real Valladolid]].\n\nIn [[1985 CONCACAF Championship qualification]], El Salvador beat [[Puerto Rico national football team|Puerto Rico]] 8\u20130 on aggregate (5\u20130, 3\u20130) to qualify for the [[1985 CONCACAF Championship|final tournament]]. They were placed in a group with Honduras and [[Suriname national football team|Suriname]], with the top team advancing. They finished second in the group with five points,<ref name=\"cm\"/> one point behind Honduras. In [[1989 CONCACAF Championship qualification]] they eliminated the [[Netherlands Antilles national football team|Netherlands Antilles]] 6\u20130 on aggregate (1\u20130, 5\u20130). El Salvador finished last, with just two points, in the round-robin [[1989 CONCACAF Championship|final tournament]].<ref name=\"cm\"/>\n\n===1990s===\nAt a CONCACAF congress, held in [[Guatemala]] on 26 January 1991, a new tournament, called the [[UNCAF Nations Cup]], was conceived for Central American teams. The inaugural tournament was hosted in [[1991 UNCAF Nations Cup|1991]], hosted by [[Costa Rica]]. The tournament also doubled as qualification for the [[CONCACAF Gold Cup]], a new tournament which replaced the [[CONCACAF Championship]].<ref name=\"uncaf\">{{cite web | title=El Salvador en UNCAF  |language=Spanish | url= http://www.elbaloncuscatleco.com/uncaf.html | publisher=Elbaloncuscatleco.com | accessdate=2011-04-21 | date=}}</ref><ref name=\"Gold Cup 1991\">{{cite web | author=Mazet, Fran\u00e7ois |title=CONCACAF Championship, Gold Cup 1991 | url= http://www.rsssf.com/tables/91gc.html | publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]] | accessdate=16 May 2011 | date=9 July 2001}}</ref> In qualification, ''La Selecta'' defeated [[Nicaragua national football team|Nicaragua]] 5\u20132 on aggregate (3\u20132, 2\u20130) and advanced to the final tournament. In the finals, they played three games, drawing one and losing two, finishing in last place and failing to advance to the [[1991 CONCACAF Gold Cup]].<ref name=\"uncaf\" /> The [[1993 UNCAF Nations Cup]] once again served as qualification to the Gold Cup, this time for the [[1993 CONCACAF Gold Cup]].<ref name=\"uncaf\"/> Coached by [[Jorge Vieira (Brazilian footballer)|Jorge Vieira]], ''La Selecta'' advanced to the final tournament automatically. There they played three games, once again drawing one and losing two to finish last and fail to advance to the Gold Cup.<ref name=\"uncaf\"/>\n\nIn [[1994 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONCACAF)|1994 World Cup qualification]], El Salvador eliminated Nicaragua 10\u20131 on aggregate (5\u20130, 5\u20131) in the first round, then finished first in a group composed of [[Bermuda national football team|Bermuda]] (0\u20131, 4\u20131), Canada (1\u20131, 3\u20132), and [[Jamaica national football team|Jamaica]] (2\u20130, 2\u20131) in the second round. In the third round, El Salvador began with a win against Mexico at home, but lost their next four games, including two defeats against Canada. They beat Honduras 2\u20131 at home in their final game, but finished third in the group and were eliminated.\n\nEl Salvador hosted the [[1995 UNCAF Nations Cup]]. In their first round, they topped a group containing Costa Rica and [[Belize national football team|Belize]], and lost 1\u20130 to Guatemala in the knockout round. They won the third place match 2\u20131 against Costa Rica and advanced to the [[1996 CONCACAF Gold Cup]] alongside Guatemala and the tournament winners, Honduras.<ref name=\"1996qr1afa\">{{cite web|title=UNCAF Tournament 1995 |language=Spanish |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesg/gold-cam95.html |work=rsssf.com |accessdate=2015-09-26 |date=2001-11-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110514025907/http://www.rsssf.com/tablesg/gold-cam95.html |archivedate=2011-05-14 }}</ref> This was their first appearance at the Gold Cup.<ref name=\"uncaf\"/><ref name=\"UNCAF Nations Cup 1995\"/> At the finals of the 1996 Gold Cup, El Salvador defeated [[Trinidad and Tobago national football team|Trinidad and Tobago]] 3\u20132, with goals from [[Ra\u00fal D\u00edaz Arce]] (2) and [[Ronald Cerritos]] in their first game, but then lost 2\u20130 to the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]] and did not advance from the first round.<ref name=\"concacaf\">{{cite web | title=El Salvador en CONCACAF  |language=Spanish | url= http://www.elbaloncuscatleco.com/concacaf.html | publisher=Elbaloncuscatleco.com | accessdate=2011-04-21 | date=}}</ref><ref name=\"Gold Cup 1996\">{{cite web | author=Stokkermans, Karel |title=CONCACAF Championship, Gold Cup 1996 | url= http://www.rsssf.com/tables/96gc.html | publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]] | accessdate=16 May 2011 | date=22 October 2001}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[1997 UNCAF Nations Cup]], hosted in Guatemala, El Salvador lost 3\u20130 to Honduras in their first match but defeated Panama 2\u20130 in their second. In the second group stage they finished in third place, losing 1\u20130 to both Guatemala and Costa Rica, and drawing 0\u20130 against Honduras. They advanced to the [[1998 CONCACAF Gold Cup]], hosted in the [[United States]].<ref name=\"uncaf\"/><ref name=\"UNCAF Nations Cup 1997\"/> El Salvador were coached by [[Kiril Dojcinovski]]. In the group stage, they drew 0\u20130 with Guatemala, and lost to Brazil (4\u20130) and Jamaica (2\u20130).<ref name=\"concacaf\"/><ref name=\"Gold Cup 1998\">{{cite web | author=Stokkermans, Karel |title=CONCACAF Championship, Gold Cup 1998 | url= http://www.rsssf.com/tables/98gc.html | publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]] | accessdate=16 May 2011 | date=22 October 2001}}</ref>\n\nIn [[1998 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONCACAF)|1998 World Cup qualification]], El Salvador received a bye to the third round, where they were drawn into a group with Canada, Cuba, and Panama. They finished second behind Canada and advanced to the six-team final round. El Salvador finished in fifth place with two wins, four draws, and four defeats.<ref name=\"cm\"/> This was the closest they had come to qualifying for a World Cup since 1982.\n\nAt the [[1999 UNCAF Nations Cup]], hosted in Costa Rica, El Salvador drew 1\u20131 with Guatemala and defeated Nicaragua 1\u20130 in the first round, with Magdonio Corrales scoring in both games. In the second group stage, they lost 3\u20131 to Honduras, 1\u20130 Guatemala and 4\u20130 to Costa Rica to finish bottom of the group, and failed to advance to the [[2000 CONCACAF Gold Cup]]. They were coached by [[Marinho Peres|Mario Peres Ulibarri]].<ref name=\"UNCAF Nations Cup 1999\">{{cite web|author=Courtney, Barrie |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesg/gold-cam99.html | title= Qualifying Tournament for Gold Cup 1999 | publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]] | accessdate=16 May 2011 | date=2 Mar 2005}}</ref>\n\n===2000s===\nIn [[2002 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONCACAF)|2002 World Cup qualification]], El Salvador topped a first round group ahead of Belize and Guatemala, but finished third behind and [[Jamaica national football team|Jamaica]] in the second round, and were eliminated.<ref name=\"2002 World Cup qualify\">{{cite web|author=Stokkermans, Karel |url=http://rsssf.com/tables/2002q.html#nca | title= World Cup 2002 Qualifying | publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]] | accessdate=16 May 2011 | date=26 November 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2001 UNCAF Nations Cup]] in Honduras, El Salvador topped their first-round group, defeating Nicaragua 3\u20130, Panama 2\u20131, and drawing 1\u20131 with the hosts. In the final round they drew all their games to finish third and advance to the [[2002 CONCACAF Gold Cup]]. They were coached by [[Carlos Recinos]].<ref name=\"uncaf\"/><ref name=\"UNCAF Nations Cup 2001\"/> In the Gold Cup, El Salvador lost their first match in Group A to Mexico (1\u20130), but defeated Guatemala by the same score, with a goal from [[Santos Cabrera]]. This allowed them to advance to the quarter-finals of the Gold Cup for the first time, but they lost 4\u20130 at that stage to the eventual champions, the United States.<ref name=\"concacaf\"/><ref name=\"Gold Cup 2002\">{{cite web | author=Gonzalez, Miguel Alvin |title=CONCACAF Championship, Gold Cup 2002 | url= http://www.rsssf.com/tables/02gc.html | publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]] | accessdate=16 May 2011 | date=29 April 2002}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2003 UNCAF Nations Cup]] in [[Panama]], El Salvador finished third again, with [[Juan Ram\u00f3n Paredes]] as head coach. In the tournament, they won 2\u20131 against Panama, lost 1\u20130 to Costa Rica, beat Nicaragua 3\u20130 and Honduras 1\u20130, and lost 2\u20130 against Guatemala. They qualified for the [[2003 CONCACAF Gold Cup]],<ref name=\"UNCAF Nations Cup 2003\"/> where they were drawn into Group C with [[Martinique national football team|Martinique]] and the United States. El Salvador 2\u20130 lost to the United States but beat Martinique 1\u20130 with a goal from [[Marvin Gonz\u00e1lez]]. In the quarter-finals, they were beaten 5\u20132 by Costa Rica, with three of the seven goals coming from penalty kicks.<ref name=\"concacaf\"/><ref name=\"Gold Cup 2003\">{{cite web |title=CONCACAF Championship, Gold Cup 2003 | url= http://www.rsssf.com/tables/03gc.html | publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]] | accessdate=16 May 2011 | date=5 Mar 2005}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2006 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONCACAF)|2006 World Cup qualifiers]] and [[2005 UNCAF Nations Cup]], hosted in [[Guatemala]], were both huge disasters for El Salvador. In the former they received a bye to the second round, where they inched past [[Bermuda national football team|Bermuda]] 4\u20133 on aggregate (2\u20131, 2\u20132). In the third round they finished last in a group that contained Jamaica, Panama and the United States, with just four points from six games.<ref name=\"2006 World Cup qualify\">{{cite web|author1=Karel Stokkermans |author2=Lars Aarhus |author3=Jim Goloboy |author4=Ian King |author5=Jarek Owsianski |author6=Malik Riaz Hai Naveed |author7=Juli\u00e1n D\u00edaz Rubio |author8=Mart\u00edn Tabeira |author9=Antonio Zea |author10=Andre Zlotkowski |url=http://rsssf.com/tables/2006q.html#nca | title= World Cup 2006 Qualifying | publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]] | accessdate=16 May 2011 | date=26 November 2009}}</ref> In the 2005 UNCAF Nations Cup they went out in the first round after losing against Panama (1\u20130) and Costa Rica (2\u20131), which meant they also failed to qualify for the [[2005 CONCACAF Gold Cup]]. They were coached by [[Carlos Cavagnaro]].<ref name=\"UNCAF Nations Cup 2005\">{{cite web |author=Courtney, Barrie |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesg/gold-cam05det.html |title=Qualifying Tournament for Gold Cup 2005&nbsp;\u2013 Details |publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]] |accessdate=16 May 2011 |date=2 Mar 2005 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090402133826/http://rsssf.com/tablesg/gold-cam05det.html |archivedate=2 April 2009}}</ref>\n\nCoached by [[Carlos de los Cobos]], El Salvador hosted the [[2007 UNCAF Nations Cup]], and won their first-round group after 2\u20131 wins over Belize and Nicaragua, and a 0\u20130 draw with Guatemala. In the semi-finals, they lost 1\u20130 to the eventual champions, Costa Rica, and finished the tournament in fourth after Guatemala beat them by the same scored in the third place play-off.<ref name=\"UNCAF Nations Cup 2007\">{{cite web|author=Courtney, Barrie |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesg/gold-cam07det.html |title=Qualifying Tournament for Gold Cup 2007&nbsp;\u2013 Details |publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]] |accessdate=16 May 2011 |date=2 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081024034751/http://www.rsssf.com/tablesg/gold-cam07det.html |archivedate=24 October 2008 }}</ref> This allowed them to qualify for the [[2007 CONCACAF Gold Cup]], where they began with a 2\u20131 win against Trinidad and Tobago 2\u20131, with goals from [[Ram\u00f3n S\u00e1nchez]] and [[Dennis Alas]]. They lost their next two matches against Guatemala (1\u20130) and the United States (4\u20130) and exited the tournament.<ref name=\"Gold Cup 2007\">{{cite web |title=CONCACAF Championship, Gold Cup 2007 | url= http://www.rsssf.com/tables/07gc.html | publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]] | accessdate=16 May 2011 | date=29 January 2009}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 June 2007, El Salvador met Hungary at the [[Estadio Cuscatl\u00e1n]] in a repeat of their match at the 1982 World Cup. Many of the same players that had played the original World Cup match played again. The match was drawn 2\u20132, with goals from [[L\u00e1z\u00e1r Szentes]] and [[Ferenc Csongr\u00e1di]] for Hungary and two goals from Luis Ram\u00edrez Zapata for El Salvador.<ref>{{cite web|last=Gomez|first=Omar|title=Los Mundialistas del '82 en el 2007|url=http://www.elbaloncuscatleco.com/cm82-2007.html|publisher=elbaoncuscatleco.com|accessdate=28 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2009 UNCAF Nations Cup]] in [[Honduras]], El Salvador finished second in their group after Belize 4\u20131, drawing 1\u20131 with Nicaragua and losing 2\u20130 to Honduras, and Nicaragua. Their semi-final against Costa Rica was called off after 60 minutes, with Costa Rica leading 1\u20130, when El Salvador were reduced to six players.[[Alexander Escobar]] and [[Eliseo Quintanilla]] were sent off in the first half, while [[Deris Umanzor]], [[Rodolfo Zelaya]] and their goalkeeper [[Juan Jos\u00e9 G\u00f3mez]] were injured and had to leave the field after El Salvador had already used their three substitutions. The game was awarded as a 3\u20130 win to Costa Rica. In the third place play-off, they lost 1\u20130 to Honduras after a goal by [[Roger Espinoza]].<ref name=\"UNCAF Nations Cup 2009\">{{cite web|author=Lugo, Erik Francisco  |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesg/gold-cam09.html | title= UNCAF Nations Cup 2009 | publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]] | accessdate=16 May 2011 | date=28 Oct 2010}}</ref> At the [[2009 CONCACAF Gold Cup]], El Salvador began by beating Costa Rica 2\u20131, with two goals by [[Osael Romero]]. However, they lost 1\u20130 against Canada and Jamaica and were eliminated.<ref name=\"Gold Cup 2009\">{{cite web |title=CONCACAF Championship, Gold Cup 2009 | url= http://www.rsssf.com/tables/09gc.html | publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]] | accessdate=16 May 2011 | date=25 March 2011}}</ref>\n\n===2010s===\nIn [[2010 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONCACAF)|2010 World Cup qualification]] El Salvador beat [[Anguilla national football team|Anguilla]] 16\u20130 on aggregate and Panama 3\u20132 on aggregate in the first two rounds. In their third round group, they finished second in the group behind Costa Rica, ahead of Haiti and [[Suriname national football team|Suriname]], to advance to the ''Hexagonal'' round. Despite drawing against the United States and beating Mexico, El Salvador finished in fifth place and were eliminated. [[Rudis Corrales]] was their top scorer in qualification with 8 goals.<ref name=\"2010 World Cup qualify\">{{cite web|author1=Ian King |author2=Erik Francisco Lugo |author3=Karel Stokkermans |author4=Andre Zlotkowski |url=http://rsssf.com/tables/2010q.html#nca | title= World Cup 2010 Qualifying | publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]] | accessdate=16 May 2011 | date=28 October 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 May 2010, the [[FIFA Emergency Committee]] suspended the [[Salvadoran Football Federation]] (FESFUT) on account of government interference, as the statutes ratified by the FESFUT general assembly in August 2009 had not been entered in the country's official register, and that the government had failed to acknowledge the authority of the Normalisation Committee set up to represent FESFUT.<ref name=\"Suspension1\">{{cite web | title= Suspension of the Salvadoran Football Association | url= https://www.fifa.com/aboutfifa/organisation/news/newsid=1209619/ | publisher=[[FIFA]] | accessdate=2010-11-12 | date=2010-04-12}}</ref> The suspension was lifted by 28 May 28, allowing ''La Selecta'' to participate in international tournaments. El Salvador's [[El Salvador national under-21 football team|under-21 team]] qualified for the [[2010 Central American and Caribbean Games]] (CAC) in Mayag\u00fcez, Puerto Rico. However, CONCACAF decided to suspend football at the 2010 CAC shortly after. El Salvador were also able to participate in the [[2012 CONCACAF Men's Olympic Qualifying Championship|qualifying tournament]] for the [[2012 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"Suspension2\">{{cite web | title= Suspension of Salvadoran Football Association lifted | url= https://www.fifa.com/aboutfifa/organisation/news/newsid=1220034/ | publisher=[[FIFA]] | accessdate=2010-11-12 | date=2010-04-27}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2011 Copa Centroamericana]], the new version of the reorganized UNCAF Nations Cup, El Salvador qualified from their first-round group in second place after defeating Nicaragua 2\u20130 and Belize 5\u20132, and losing 2\u20130 against Panama. In the semi-finals they lost 2\u20130 to Honduras, and lost 5\u20134 in a penalty shootout to Panama, after a 0\u20130 draw. This performance qualified El Salvador for the [[2011 CONCACAF Gold Cup]]. The team was coached by [[Jos\u00e9 Luis Rugamas]]. Forward [[Rafael Burgos (footballer)|Rafael Burgos]] jointly received the Golden Boot with Costa Rica's [[Marco Ure\u00f1a]], with three goals.<ref name=\"2011 Copa Centroamericana\">{{cite web|author=Lugo, Erik Francisco |author2=Torres, Steven |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesg/gold-cam2011.html |title=2011 Copa Centroamericana |publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]] |accessdate=16 May 2011 |date=25 March 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105045831/http://www.rsssf.com/tablesg/gold-cam2011.html |archivedate=5 November 2013 }}</ref>\n\nIn April 2011, two months before the start of the Gold Cup, Jos\u00e9 Luis Rugamas was replaced as coach by [[Rub\u00e9n Israel]].<ref name=\"New coach\">{{cite web |url=http://www.elsalvadorfc.com/2011-04-06-israel-hemos-venido-a-honrar-el-trabajo |title='We have come to honor the work,' Israel |language=Spanish |publisher=elsalvadorfc.com |accessdate=2011-04-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130102144428/http://www.elsalvadorfc.com/2011-04-06-israel-hemos-venido-a-honrar-el-trabajo |archivedate=2013-01-02 }}</ref> At the Gold Cup, El Salvador began with a 5\u20130 defeat to Mexico.<ref name=\"2011 CONCACAF Gold Cup - Mexico\">{{cite web|author= McCauley, Kevin |url=https://www.sbnation.com/soccer/2011/6/5/2208429/mexico-vs-el-salvador-2011-gold-cup-final-score-copa-oro-chicharito-el-tri | title= Mexico Vs. El Salvador, 2011 Gold Cup: Final Score, El Tri Win 5\u20130; 'Chicharito' Javier Hernandez Nets Hat Trick | publisher=sbnation.com  | accessdate=17 June 2011 | date=5 June 2011}}</ref> They drew 1\u20131 with Costa Rica, with [[Rodolfo Zelaya]]'s 25-yard free-kick opener being equalised by a Costa Rican goal in injury time,<ref name=\"2011 CONCACAF Gold Cup - Costa Rica\">{{cite web|author= McCauley, Kevin |url=https://www.sbnation.com/soccer/2011/6/9/2216543/costa-rica-vs-el-salvador-final-score-copa-oro-2011-gold-cup | title= Costa Rica Vs. El Salvador Final Score, Gold Cup 2011: Ticos Snatch Late Draw | publisher=sbnation.com  | accessdate=17 June 2011 | date=9 June 2011}}</ref>) and beat Cuba 6\u20131 to reach the knockout stage for the first time since 2003.<ref name=\"2011 CONCACAF Gold Cup - Cuba\">{{cite web |author= Lewis, Michael |url= http://www.goldcup.org/page/GoldCup/NewsDetail/0,,12802~2378368,00.html |title= El Salvador ignoring past against Panama |publisher= goldcup.org |accessdate= 17 June 2011 |date= 17 June 2011 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110619012316/http://www.goldcup.org/page/GoldCup/NewsDetail/0,,12802~2378368,00.html |archive-date= 19 June 2011 |url-status= dead }}</ref><ref name=\"2011 CONCACAF Gold Cup\">{{cite web|author=Lugo, Erik Francisco |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tables/2011gc.html | title= 2011 CONCACAF Championship, Gold Cup 2011 | publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]] | accessdate=17 June 2011 | date=16 June 2011}}</ref> In the quarter-finals they drew 1\u20131 with Panama, with Panama scoring a controversial equaliser through [[Luis Tejada]] one minute from the end. Their coach Israel called the decision an \"error of haste.\"<ref name=\"2011 CONCACAF Gold Cup - Error\">{{cite web|author=Hern\u00e1ndez, Diego |url=http://www.goal.com/es-us/news/3443/el-salvador/2011/06/20/2540555/copa-oro-debemos-la-eliminaci%C3%B3n-a-un-error-humano-se%C3%B1al%C3%B3 | title= \"Debemos la eliminaci\u00f3n a un error humano\", se\u00f1al\u00f3 Israel  | publisher=goal.com | accessdate=19 June 2011 | date=19 June 2011 |language=Spanish |trans-title=\"We owe the elimination to a human error\", says Israel}}</ref> Panama won the penalty shoot-out 5\u20133.<ref name=\"2011 CONCACAF Gold Cup - Panama\">{{cite web |author=CONCACAF |url=http://www.concacaf.com/page/GoldCup/NewsDetail/0,,12813~2378721,00.html |title=Panama returns to Gold Cup semifinals |publisher=CONCACAF.com |accessdate=19 June 2011 |date=19 June 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110624184540/http://www.concacaf.com/page/GoldCup/NewsDetail/0,,12813~2378721,00.html |archive-date=24 June 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn [[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONCACAF)|2014 World Cup qualification]], El Salvador received a bye to the second round, where they began with a 3\u20132 win against the [[Dominican Republic national football team|Dominican Republic]], with goals scored by [[Rodolfo Zelaya]] (2) and [[Christian Javier Bautista]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Triunfo bueno, marcador enga\u00f1oso|url=http://www.elgrafico.com/gol-nacional/13-gol-nacional/17397-el-salvador-0-0-dominicana-primer-tiempo.html|publisher=elgrafico.com|accessdate=7 September 2011|language=Spanish}}</ref> They then beat the [[Cayman Islands national football team|Cayman Islands]] 4\u20131 with goals from Bautista, [[Luis Anaya]] (2) and [[Xavier Garc\u00eda (footballer)|Xavier Garc\u00eda]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Arteaga|first=Ernesto|title=Anaya, goleador inesperado|url=http://www.elgrafico.com/destacado-portada/36-destacadas/17557-anaya-goleador-inesperado.html|publisher=elgrafico.com|accessdate=7 September 2011|language=Spanish}}</ref> before winning the return against the Dominican Republic 2\u20131. <ref>{{cite web|title=Otra victoria con susto|url=http://www.elgrafico.com/gol-nacional/13-gol-nacional/18663-dominicana-0-0-el-salvador.html|work=elgrafico.com|accessdate=14 October 2011|language=Spanish}}</ref> They beat the Cayman Islands 4\u20130 at home, with goals by [[V\u00edctor Turcios]], [[Steve Purdy]], [[Jaime Alas]] and [[Herbert Sosa]]. The last of these was the thousandth goal scored by the national team.<ref>{{cite web|title=El Salvador gana y llega a mil goles|url=http://www.elgrafico.com/gol-nacional/13-gol-nacional/18797-el-salvador-0-0-islas-caiman-primer-tiempo.html|work=elgrafico.com|accessdate=14 October 2011|language=Spanish}}</ref> Two comfortable wins over Suriname gave them a perfect record of six wins in six matches.\n\nIn the next round, El Salvador snatched a draw against Costa Rica in [[San Jos\u00e9 (Costa Rica)|San Jos\u00e9]] after being 2\u20130 down, but a home defeat against Mexico four days later precipitated the departure of Israel, whose poor relations with [[Jaime Rodr\u00edguez]], the president of the National Institute of Sport Salvador (INDES) were widely known. The [[Salvadoran Football Association]] (FESFUT) named the Mexican [[Juan de Dios Castillo]] as his replacement.\nDespite a good start, a 1\u20130 win in a friendly match against [[Guatemala national football team|Guatemala]], a 2\u20132 draw at the Estadio Cuscatl\u00e1n in a qualifier against modest [[Guyana national football team|Guyana]] earned him the wrath of the public.{{cn|date=April 2020}} A 3\u20132 victory in [[Georgetown, Guyana|Georgetown]], with a penalty saved by El Salvador's goalkeeper [[Dagoberto Portillo]] in additional time, allowed kept their qualifying hopes alive, but these were ended by a 1\u20130 home defeat against Costa Rica. Juan de Dios Castillo was sacked in November 2012 and replaced on 17 December by the Peruvian [[Agust\u00edn Castillo]], a five-time national champion with [[C.D. FAS]].\n\nEl Salvador finished third in the [[2013 Copa Centroamericana]], allowing them to qualify for the [[2013 CONCACAF Gold Cup]] in the United States. In that tournament, a 1\u20130 win over Haiti allowed them to qualify from the group stages in third place, but they lost 5\u20131 to the host nation in the quarter-finals.\n\nIn [[2018 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONCACAF)|2018 World Cup qualification]], El Salvador won knockout ties against [[Saint Kitts and Nevis national football team|Saint Kitts and Nevis]] and [[Cura\u00e7ao national football team|Cura\u00e7ao]] to reach the fourth round group stage, but they finished bottom of a group containing Mexico, Honduras and Canada with two draws and four defeats from their six matches.\n\n===Match fixing===\nThe national team had accusations of several players purposely losing matches on purpose in exchange for monetary rewards. Some of these allegations involved games against [[Venezuela national football team|Venezuela]], [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]], [[United States men's national soccer team|USA]], and [[Costa Rica national football team|Costa Rica]]. After an investigation, 14 players were handed immediate lifetime bans from football on September 20, 2013. Those players were [[Luis Anaya]], [[Osael Romero]], [[Ram\u00f3n S\u00e1nchez]], [[Christian Castillo (footballer)|Christian Castillo]], [[Jos\u00e9 Miguel Granadino|Miguel Granadino]], [[Miguel Montes]], [[Dagoberto Portillo]], [[Dennis Alas]], [[Darwin Bonilla]], [[Ram\u00f3n Flores (footballer)|Ram\u00f3n Flores]], [[Alfredo Pacheco]], [[Jos\u00e9 Henr\u00edquez|Jos\u00e9 Mardoqueo Henr\u00edquez]], [[Marvin Gonz\u00e1lez]], and [[Reynaldo Antonio Hern\u00e1ndez|Reynaldo Hern\u00e1ndez]]. [[Carlos Monteagudo]] received a ban of 18 months. [[Eliseo Quintanilla]] and [[V\u00edctor Turcios]] received 6 month bans. [[Alexander Escobar]], [[Christian S\u00e1nchez (Salvadoran footballer)|Christian S\u00e1nchez]], and U-20 goalkeeper Yimmy Cuellar received a ban of 30 days. Other players were forced to go through the investigation for 20 more days. After the 20-day investigation, Rodrigo Mart\u00ednez was sentenced to a ban of 5 years, [[Rodolfo Zelaya]] to a ban of one year, and [[Benji Villalobos]] to a ban of 6 months.\n\nOn 6 September 2016, the team revealed that they had all been approached, and had turned down, an offer to ensure that their result against [[Canada men's national soccer team|Canada]] saw [[Honduras national football team|Honduras]] progress to the [[2018 FIFA World Cup qualification&nbsp;\u2013 CONCACAF Fifth Round|next round]],<ref>{{cite web|title=World Cup 2018 qualifying: El Salvador 'refuse bribe to fix match'|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/37284033|website=bbc.co.uk|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=6 September 2016|date=6 September 2016}}</ref> but then-coach [[Ramon Maradiaga]] was later fined 20,000 Swiss francs and banned from football for two years for not disclosing the approach.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fifa bans former El Salvador coach for two years for involvement in match-fixing case|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/43981077|website=bbc.co.uk|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=10 October 2018|date=2 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Competitive record==\n===FIFA World Cup===\n{{main|El Salvador at the FIFA World Cup}}\nEl Salvador has never advanced beyond the first round of the finals competition. El Salvador declined to participate at the 1950 FIFA World Cup.<ref name=\"Withdrew\" group=\"note\" />\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!colspan=9|[[FIFA World Cup]] record\n!width=1% rowspan=26|\n!colspan=6|[[FIFA World Cup qualification]] record\n|-\n!Year\n!Round\n!Position\n!{{Tooltip|Pld|Games played}}\n!{{Tooltip|W|Won}}\n!{{Tooltip|D|Drawn}}*\n!{{Tooltip|L|Lost}}\n!{{Tooltip|GF|Goals for}}\n!{{Tooltip|GA|Goals against}}\n!{{Tooltip|Pld|Games played}}\n!{{Tooltip|W|Won}}\n!{{Tooltip|D|Drawn}}\n!{{Tooltip|L|Lost}}\n!{{Tooltip|GF|Goals for}}\n!{{Tooltip|GA|Goals against}}\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Uruguay}} [[1930 FIFA World Cup|1930]]||colspan=8 rowspan=2|''Did not enter''\n|colspan=6 rowspan=2|''Did not enter''\n|- \n| {{flagicon|Italy|1861}} [[1934 FIFA World Cup|1934]]\n|-\n| {{flagicon|France|1794}} [[1938 FIFA World Cup|1938]]||colspan=8 rowspan=2|''Withdrew'' <ref name=\"Withdrew\" group=\"note\" />\n|colspan=6 rowspan=2|''Withdrew''\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Brazil|1889}} [[1950 FIFA World Cup|1950]]\n|- \n| {{flagicon|Switzerland}} [[1954 FIFA World Cup|1954]]||colspan=8 rowspan=4|''Did not enter''\n|colspan=6 rowspan=4|''Did not enter''\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Sweden}} [[1958 FIFA World Cup|1958]]\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Chile}} [[1962 FIFA World Cup|1962]]\n|-\n| {{flagicon|England}} [[1966 FIFA World Cup|1966]]\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Mexico}} [[1970 FIFA World Cup|1970]]\n| Group stage\n| 16th\n| 3\n| 0\n| 0\n| 3\n| 0\n| 9\n| 10\n| 7\n| 0\n| 3\n| 19\n| 12\n|-\n| {{flagicon|West Germany}} [[1974 FIFA World Cup|1974]]||colspan=8 rowspan=2|''Did not qualify''\n| 7\t\n| 3\t\n| 2\t\n| 2\t\n| 15\t\n| 9\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Argentina}} [[1978 FIFA World Cup|1978]]\n| 11\t\n| 4\t\n| 4\t\n| 3\t\n| 18\t\n| 16\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Spain}} [[1982 FIFA World Cup|1982]]\n| Group stage\n| 24th\n| 3\n| 0\n| 0\n| 3\n| 1\n| 13\n| 13\n| 7\n| 4\n| 2\n| 14\n| 6\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Mexico}} [[1986 FIFA World Cup|1986]]||colspan=8 rowspan=9|''Did not qualify''\n| 6\n| 4\n| 1\n| 1\n| 15\n| 2\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Italy}} [[1990 FIFA World Cup|1990]]\n| 8\n| 2\n| 2\n| 4\n| 8\n| 8\n|-\n| {{flagicon|United States}} [[1994 FIFA World Cup|1994]]\n| 14\t\n| 8\t\n| 1\t\n| 5\t\n| 28\t\n| 11\n|-\n| {{flagicon|France}} [[1998 FIFA World Cup|1998]]\n| 16\n| 5\t\n| 5\t\n| 6\t\n| 23\n| 22\n|-\n| {{flagicon|South Korea|1997}} {{flagicon|Japan}} [[2002 FIFA World Cup|2002]]\n| 10\t\n| 6\t\n| 1\t\n| 3\t\n| 23\t\n| 15\t\t\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Germany}} [[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006]]\n| 8\t\n| 3\t\n| 1\t\n| 4\t\n| 6\t\n| 14\n|-\n| {{flagicon|South Africa}} [[2010 FIFA World Cup|2010]]\n| 20\t\n| 8\t\n| 3\t\n| 9\t\n| 39\t\n| 21\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Brazil}} [[2014 FIFA World Cup|2014]]\n| 12\t\n| 7\t\n| 2\t\n| 3\t\n| 28\t\n| 16\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Russia}} [[2018 FIFA World Cup|2018]]\n| 10\n| 3\n| 3\t\n| 4\t\n| 12\n| 16\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Qatar}} [[2022 FIFA World Cup|2022]]\n|colspan=8 rowspan=2|''To be determined''\n|colspan=6 rowspan=2|''To be determined''\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Canada}} {{flagicon|Mexico}} {{flagicon|United States}} [[2026 FIFA World Cup|2026]]\n|-\n!Total\n!Group stage\n!2/21\n!6\n!0\n!0\n!6\n!1\n!22\n!140\n!64\n!27\n!47\n!233\n!161\n|}\n:''*Denotes draws include knockout matches decided on [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty kicks]].''\n:''**Red border color indicates tournament was held on home soil.''\n\n===CONCACAF Gold Cup===\n{{main|El Salvador at the CONCACAF Gold Cup}}\nIn 1963 El Salvador participated in the first CONCACAF Championship which included all countries of the region, North America, Central America and the Caribbean. During 1963 to 1971 only 5 championships were played. El Salvador achieving only a runner-up in 1963. From 1973 to 1989 no championship was played. The CONCACAF proclaimed champion of the region for the country that achieved the first place in qualifying to the FIFA World Cup. In 1990, CONCACAF again created a tournament as its showpiece event to crown the regional champion of the CONCACAF. The event was named the CONCACAF Gold Cup, with the US hosting the first competition in 1991. In the 2002, 2003, and 2011 events El Salvador reached the quarter-finals.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!colspan=10|[[CONCACAF Championship]] / [[CONCACAF Gold Cup|Gold Cup]] record \n|-\n!Year\n!Round\n!{{Tooltip|Pld|Games played}}\n!{{Tooltip|W|Won}}\n!{{Tooltip|D|Drawn}}*\n!{{Tooltip|L|Lost}}\n!{{Tooltip|GF|Goals for}}\n!{{Tooltip|GA|Goals against}}\n|- style=\"background:silver;\"\n|style=\"border: 3px solid red\"|{{Flagicon|El Salvador}} [[1963 CONCACAF Championship|1963]]||Runners-up||7||3||3||1||17||7\n|- style=\"background:LemonChiffon;\"\n| {{flagicon|Guatemala}} [[1965 CONCACAF Championship|1965]]||Fourth place||5||2||1||2||7||9\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Honduras}} [[1967 CONCACAF Championship|1967]]||colspan=7|''Did not enter''\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Costa Rica}} [[1969 CONCACAF Championship|1969]]||colspan=7|''Banned''\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Trinidad and Tobago}} [[1971 CONCACAF Championship|1971]]||colspan=7|''Withdrew''\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Haiti|1964}} [[1973 CONCACAF Championship|1973]]||colspan=7|''Did not qualify''\n|- style=\"background:#c96;\"\n| {{flagicon|Mexico}} [[1977 CONCACAF Championship|1977]]||Third place||5||2||1||2||8||9\n|- style=\"background:silver;\"\n| {{flagicon|Honduras}} [[1981 CONCACAF Championship|1981]]||Runners-up||5||2||2||1||2||1\n|- style=\"background:LemonChiffon;\"\n| [[1985 CONCACAF Championship|1985]]||Fourth place||4||2||1||1||7||2\n|-\n| [[1989 CONCACAF Championship|1989]]||Fifth place||6||0||2||4||2||8\n|-\n| {{flagicon|United States}} [[1991 CONCACAF Gold Cup|1991]]||colspan=7 rowspan=2|''Did not qualify''\n|-\n| {{f